# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: encodings-serialization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ASCII encodes each code-point as a value from 0 to 127 – storable as a seven-bit integer.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Ninety-five code-points are printable, including digits *0* to *9*, lowercase letters *a* to *z*, uppercase letters *A* to *Z*, and commonly used punctuation symbols.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] For example, the letter `i` is represented as 105 (decimal).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Also, ASCII specifies 33 non-printing control codes which originated with Teletype devices, most of which are now obsolete.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The control characters that are still commonly used include carriage return, line feed, and tab.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ASCII lacks code-points for characters with diacritical marks and therefore does not directly support terms or names such as résumé, jalapeño, or René.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] But, depending on hardware and software support, some diacritical marks can be rendered by overwriting a letter with a backtick (`) or tilde (~).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) prefers the name **US-ASCII** for this character encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ASCII is the standardisation of a seven-bit teleprinter code developed in part from earlier telegraph codes.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Work on the ASCII standard began in May 1961, when IBM engineer Bob Bemer submitted a proposal to the American Standards Association's (ASA) (now the American National Standards Institute or ANSI) X3.2 subcommittee.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The first edition of the standard was published in 1963, contemporaneously with the introduction of the Teletype Model 33.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] It later underwent a major revision in 1967, and several further revisions until 1986.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In contrast to earlier telegraph codes such as Baudot, ASCII was ordered for more convenient collation (especially alphabetical sorting of lists), and added controls for devices other than teleprinters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ASCII was developed under the auspices of a committee of the American Standards Association (ASA), called the X3 committee, by its X3.2 (later X3L2) subcommittee, and later by that subcommittee's X3.2.4 working group (now INCITS).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The ASA later became the United States of America Standards Institute (USASI) and ultimately became the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] With the other special characters and control codes filled in, ASCII was published as ASA X3.4-1963, leaving 28 code positions without any assigned meaning, reserved for future standardization, and one unassigned control code.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] There was some debate at the time whether there should be more control characters rather than the lowercase alphabet.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The indecision did not last long: during May 1963 the CCITT Working Party on the New Telegraph Alphabet proposed to assign lowercase characters to *sticks* 6 and 7, and International Organization for Standardization TC 97 SC 2 voted during October to incorporate the change into its draft standard.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The X3.2.4 task group voted its approval for the change to ASCII at its May 1963 meeting.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Locating the lowercase letters in *sticks* 6 and 7 caused the characters to differ in bit pattern from the upper case by a single bit, which simplified case-insensitive character matching and the construction of keyboards and printers.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] It added the brace and vertical bar characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] It renamed some control characters – SOM became SOH.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] It moved or removed others – RU was removed.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The use of ASCII format for Network Interchange was described in 1969.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] That document was formally elevated to an Internet Standard in 2015.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In the X3.15 standard, the X3 committee also addressed how ASCII should be transmitted (least significant bit first) and recorded on perforated tape.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] They proposed a 9-track standard for magnetic tape and attempted to deal with some punched card formats.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The X3.2 subcommittee designed ASCII based on the earlier teleprinter encoding systems.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Like other character encodings, ASCII specifies a correspondence between digital bit patterns and character symbols (i.e. graphemes and control characters).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] This allows digital devices to communicate with each other and to process, store, and communicate character-oriented information such as written language.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Before ASCII was developed, the encodings in use included 26 alphabetic characters, 10 numerical digits, and from 11 to 25 special graphic symbols.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] To include all these, and control characters compatible with the Comité Consultatif International Téléphonique et Télégraphique (CCITT) International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] 2 (ITA2) standard of 1932, FIELDATA (1956), and early EBCDIC (1963), more than 64 codes were required for ASCII.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ITA2 was in turn based on Baudot code, the 5-bit telegraph code Émile Baudot invented in 1870 and patented in 1874.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The committee debated the possibility of a shift function (like in ITA2), which would allow more than 64 codes to be represented by a six-bit code.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In a shifted code, some character codes determine choices between options for the following character codes.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] It allows compact encoding, but is less reliable for data transmission, as an error in transmitting the shift code typically makes a long part of the transmission unreadable.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The standards committee decided against shifting, and so ASCII required at least a seven-bit code.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The committee considered an eight-bit code, since eight bits (octets) would allow two four-bit patterns to efficiently encode two digits with binary-coded decimal.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] However, it would require all data transmission to send eight bits when seven could suffice.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The committee voted to use a seven-bit code to minimize costs associated with data transmission.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Since perforated tape at the time could record eight bits in one position, it also allowed for a parity bit for error checking if desired.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Eight-bit machines (with octets as the native data type) that did not use parity checking typically set the eighth bit to 0.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The code itself was patterned so that most control codes were together and all graphic codes were together, for ease of identification.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The first two so-called *ASCII sticks* (32 positions) were reserved for control characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The "space" character had to come before graphics to make sorting easier, so it became position 20hex; for the same reason, many special signs commonly used as separators were placed before digits.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The committee decided it was important to support uppercase 64-character alphabets, and chose to pattern ASCII so it could be reduced easily to a usable 64-character set of graphic codes, as was done in the DEC SIXBIT code (1963).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Lowercase letters were therefore not interleaved with uppercase.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] To keep options available for lowercase letters and other graphics, the special and numeric codes were arranged before the letters, and the letter *A* was placed in position 41hex to match the draft of the corresponding British standard.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The digits 0–9 are prefixed with 011, but the remaining 4 bits correspond to their respective values in binary, making conversion with binary-coded decimal straightforward (for example, 5 is encoded to 011*0101*, where 5 is *0101* in binary).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Many of the non-alphanumeric characters were positioned to correspond to their shifted position on typewriters; an important subtlety is that these were based on *mechanical* typewriters, not *electric* typewriters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Mechanical typewriters followed the *de facto* standard set by the Remington No.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] 2 (1878), the first typewriter with a shift key, and the shifted values of `23456789-` were `"#$%_&'()` – early typewriters omitted *0* and *1*, using *O* (capital letter *o*) and *l* (lowercase letter *L*) instead, but `1!` and `0)` pairs became standard once 0 and 1 became common.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Thus, in ASCII `!"#$%` were placed in the second stick, positions 1–5, corresponding to the digits 1–5 in the adjacent stick.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The parentheses could not correspond to *9* and *0*, however, because the place corresponding to *0* was taken by the space character.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] This was accommodated by removing `_` (underscore) from *6* and shifting the remaining characters, which corresponded to many European typewriters that placed the parentheses with *8* and *9*.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] This discrepancy from typewriters led to bit-paired keyboards, notably the Teletype Model 33, which used the left-shifted layout corresponding to ASCII, differently from traditional mechanical typewriters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] 2, and the `,< .>` pairs were used on some keyboards (others, including the No.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] 2, did not shift `,` (comma) or `.` (full stop) so they could be used in uppercase without unshifting).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] However, ASCII split the `;:` pair (dating to No.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] 2), and rearranged mathematical symbols (varied conventions, commonly `-* =+`) to `:* ;+ -=`.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Some then-common typewriter characters were not included, notably `½ ¼ ¢`, while ^ ` ~ were included as diacritics for international use, and `< >` for mathematical use, together with the simple line characters `\ |` (in addition to common `/`).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The *@* symbol was not used in continental Europe and the committee expected it would be replaced by an accented *À* in the French variation, so the *@* was placed in position 40hex, right before the letter A.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The control codes felt essential for data transmission were the start of message (SOM), end of address (EOA), end of message (EOM), end of transmission (EOT), "who are you?" (WRU), "are you?" (RU), a reserved device control (DC0), synchronous idle (SYNC), and acknowledge (ACK).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] These were positioned to maximize the Hamming distance between their bit patterns.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ASCII-code order is also called *ASCIIbetical* order.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Collation of data is sometimes done in this order rather than "standard" alphabetical order (collating sequence).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] An intermediate order converts uppercase letters to lowercase before comparing ASCII values.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ASCII reserves the first 32 code points (numbers 0–31 decimal) and the last one (number 127 decimal) for control characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] These are codes intended to control peripheral devices (such as printers), or to provide meta-information about data streams, such as those stored on magnetic tape.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Despite their name, these code points do not represent printable characters (i.e. they are not characters at all, but signals).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] For debugging purposes, "placeholder" symbols (such as those given in ISO 2047 and its predecessors) are assigned to them.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] For example, character 0x0A represents the "line feed" function (which causes a printer to advance its paper), and character 8 represents "backspace".
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] RFC 2822 refers to control characters that do not include carriage return, line feed or white space as non-whitespace control characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Except for the control characters that prescribe elementary line-oriented formatting, ASCII does not define any mechanism for describing the structure or appearance of text within a document.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Other schemes, such as markup languages, address page and document layout and formatting.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The original ASCII standard used only short descriptive phrases for each control character.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The ambiguity this caused was sometimes intentional, such as when a character would be used slightly differently on a terminal link or in a data stream.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Probably the most influential single device affecting the interpretation of these characters was the Teletype Model 33 ASR, which was a printing terminal with an available paper tape reader/punch option.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Paper tape was a very popular medium for long-term program storage until the 1980s, less costly and in some ways less fragile than magnetic tape.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In particular, the Teletype Model 33 machine assignments for codes 17 (control-Q, DC1, also known as XON), 19 (control-S, DC3, also known as XOFF), and 127 (delete) became *de facto* standards.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The Model 33 was also notable for taking the description of control-G (code 7, BEL, meaning audibly alert the operator) literally, as the unit contained an actual bell which it rang when it received a BEL character.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] When a Teletype 33 ASR equipped with the automatic paper tape reader received a control-S (XOFF, an abbreviation for transmit off), it caused the tape reader to stop; receiving control-Q (XON, transmit on) caused the tape reader to resume.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] This so-called flow control technique became adopted by several early computer operating systems as a "handshaking" signal warning a sender to stop transmission because of impending buffer overflow; it persists to this day in many systems as a manual output control technique.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] On some systems, control-S retains its meaning, but control-Q is replaced by a second control-S to resume output.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The 33 ASR also could be configured to employ control-R (DC2) and control-T (DC4) to start and stop the tape punch; on some units equipped with this function, the corresponding control character lettering on the keycap above the letter was TAPE and TAPE respectively.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The Teletype could not move its typehead backwards, so it did not have a key on its keyboard to send a BS (backspace).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Instead, there was a key marked RUB OUT that sent code 127 (DEL).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The purpose of this key was to erase mistakes in a manually-input paper tape: the operator had to push a button on the tape punch to back it up, then type the rubout, which punched all holes and replaced the mistake with a character that was intended to be ignored.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Teletypes were commonly used with the less-expensive computers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC); these systems had to use what keys were available, and thus the DEL character was assigned to erase the previous character.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Because of this, DEC video terminals (by default) sent the DEL character for the key marked "Backspace" while the separate key marked "Delete" sent an escape sequence; many other competing terminals sent a BS character for the backspace key.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The assumption that no key sent a BS character allowed Ctrl+H to be used for other purposes, such as the "help" prefix command in GNU Emacs.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Many more of the control characters have been assigned meanings quite different from their original ones.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The "escape" character (ESC, code 27), for example, was intended originally to allow sending of other control characters as literals instead of invoking their meaning, an "escape sequence".
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] This is the same meaning of "escape" encountered in URL encodings, C language strings, and other systems where certain characters have a reserved meaning.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Over time this interpretation has been co-opted and has eventually been changed.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In modern usage, an ESC sent *to* the terminal usually indicates the start of a command sequence, which can be used to address the cursor, scroll a region, set/query various terminal properties, and more.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] They are usually in the form of a so-called "ANSI escape code" (often starting with a "Control Sequence Introducer", "CSI", "ESC [") from ECMA-48 (1972) and its successors.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Some escape sequences do not have introducers, like the "Reset to Initial State", "RIS" command "ESC c".
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In contrast, an ESC read *from* the terminal is most often used as an out-of-band character used to terminate an operation or special mode, as in the TECO and vi text editors.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In graphical user interface (GUI) and windowing systems, ESC generally causes an application to abort its current operation or to exit (terminate) altogether.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The reapplication of some control characters to new meanings created problems when transferring "plain text" files between systems.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The best example of this is the newline problem in various operating systems.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Teletype machines required that a line of text be terminated with a "carriage return" (to move the printhead to the beginning of the line) followed by a "line feed" (to advance the paper by one line).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The name "carriage return" comes from the fact that, on a manual typewriter, the carriage holding the paper moves while the typebars that strike the ribbon remain stationary.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The entire carriage must be pushed to the right ("returned") in order to position the paper for the next line.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] DEC operating systems (OS/8, RT-11, RSX-11, RSTS, TOPS-10, etc.) stored both characters at the end of each line in textual files, as needed by Teletype machines.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] When so-called "glass TTYs" were introduced (later called CRTs or "dumb terminals"), they followed the same logic, expecting the same CR and LF characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] When Gary Kildall created CP/M, he was inspired by some of the command line interface conventions used in DEC's RT-11 operating system.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Until the introduction of IBM PC DOS in 1981, IBM had no influence in this, because their 1970s operating systems used EBCDIC encoding instead of ASCII and they were oriented toward punch-card input and line printer output on which the concept of "carriage return" was meaningless.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] IBM's PC DOS (also marketed as MS-DOS by Microsoft) inherited the CRLF convention by virtue of being loosely based on CP/M, and Windows, in turn, inherited it from MS-DOS.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Placing CR and LF at the end of each line in a plain text document or data stream reflects what terminals and printers needed to receive, to display that material.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Multics introduced an innovation: it used only one character (LF), to represent the end of the line in stored files and in data streams.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Upon output, the tty driver converts the LF to CRLF, so files can be printed to a terminal without needing a command to explicitly convert the file format.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Unix and Unix-like systems adopted this design from Multics, as did Amiga systems.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] UNIX documents say "newline" or "NL" to refer to the line terminator.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Contrarily, the Radio Shack TRS-80, Apple DOS, Apple ProDOS, and classic Mac OS used a lone carriage return (CR) to terminate lines.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Apple's later operating system, Mac OS X (now called macOS) is based on Unix, so it uses line feed (LF).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] To enable communication between all these systems, the Telnet protocol defined a "Network Virtual Terminal" (NVT), wherein a single text format (ASCII with CR-LF line endings) was used for transmission and each system converted to/from its own native representation.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The File Transfer Protocol adopted the Telnet protocol, including the Network Virtual Terminal, for transmitting commands and for transferring textual files (known as "ASCII mode").
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The World Wide Web's HTTP uses a modified NVT: the standard allows lone CR and LF characters but requires that each be interpreted as an NVT CRLF.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Complexity arose in network-facing systems that didn't follow the NVT mechanism, such as some version control systems.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Bugs sometimes expose a system's native implementation to other systems on the Internet, causing data corruption.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The PDP-6 monitor, and its PDP-10 successor TOPS-10, used control-Z (SUB) as an end-of-file indication for input from a terminal.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Some operating systems such as CP/M tracked file length only in units of disk blocks, and used control-Z to mark the end of the actual text in the file.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] For these reasons, EOF, or end-of-file, was used colloquially and conventionally as a three-letter acronym for control-Z instead of SUBstitute.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The end-of-text character (ETX), also known as control-C, was inappropriate for a variety of reasons, while using control-Z as the control character to end a file is analogous to the letter Z's position at the end of the alphabet, and serves as a very convenient mnemonic aid.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] A historically common and still prevalent convention uses the ETX character convention to interrupt and halt a program via an input data stream, usually from a keyboard.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The Unix terminal driver uses the end-of-transmission character (EOT), also known as control-D, to indicate the end of a data stream.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In the C programming language, and in Unix conventions, the null character is used to terminate text strings; such null-terminated strings can be known in abbreviation as ASCIZ or ASCIIZ, where here Z stands for "zero".
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Other representations might be used by specialist equipment, for example ISO 2047 graphics or hexadecimal numbers.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] At the time of adoption, the codes 20hex to 7Ehex would cause the printing of a visible character (a glyph), and thus were designated "printable characters".
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] These codes represent letters, digits, punctuation marks, and a few miscellaneous symbols.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] There are 95 printable characters in total.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The empty space between words, as produced by the space bar of a keyboard, is character code 20hex.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Since the space character is visible in printed text it considered a "printable character", even though it is unique in having no visible glyph.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] It is listed in the printable character table, as per the ASCII standard, instead of in the control character table.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Code 7Fhex corresponds to the non-printable "delete" (DEL) control character and is listed in the control character table.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Earlier versions of ASCII used the up arrow instead of the caret (5Ehex) and the left arrow instead of the underscore (5Fhex).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ASCII was first used commercially during 1963 as a seven-bit teleprinter code for American Telephone & Telegraph's TWX (TeletypeWriter eXchange) network.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] TWX originally used the earlier five-bit ITA2, which was also used by the competing Telex teleprinter system.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Bob Bemer introduced features such as the escape sequence.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] His British colleague Hugh McGregor Ross helped to popularize this work – according to Bemer, "so much so that the code that was to become ASCII was first called the *Bemer–Ross Code* in Europe".
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Because of his extensive work on ASCII, Bemer has been called "the father of ASCII".
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] On March 11, 1968, US President Lyndon B.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ASCII was the most common character encoding on the World Wide Web until December 2007, when the UTF-8 encoding surpassed it; UTF-8 is backward compatible with ASCII.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] As computer technology spread throughout the world, different standards bodies and corporations developed many variations of ASCII to facilitate the expression of non-English languages that used Roman-based alphabets.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] One could class some of these variations as "ASCII extensions", although some misuse that term to represent all variants, including those that do not preserve ASCII's character-map in the 7-bit range.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Furthermore, the ASCII extensions have also been mislabelled as ASCII.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] From early in its development, ASCII was intended to be just one of several national variants of an international character code standard.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Almost every country needed an adapted version of ASCII, since ASCII suited the needs of only the US and a few other countries.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] For example, Canada had its own version that supported French characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Many other countries developed variants of ASCII to include non-English letters (e.g. é, ñ, ß, Ł), currency symbols (e.g. £, ¥), etc.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] It would share most characters in common, but assign other locally useful characters to several code points reserved for "national use".
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ISO/IEC 646, like ASCII, is a 7-bit character set.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] It does not make any additional codes available, so the same code points encoded different characters in different countries.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] C trigraphs were created to solve this problem for ANSI C, although their late introduction and inconsistent implementation in compilers limited their use.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Many programmers kept their computers on ASCII, so plain-text in Swedish, German etc.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] (for example, in e-mail or Usenet) contained "{, }" and similar variants in the middle of words, something those programmers got used to.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] For example, a Swedish programmer mailing another programmer asking if they should go for lunch, could get "N{ jag har sm|rg}sar" as the answer, which should be "Nä jag har smörgåsar" meaning "No I've got sandwiches".
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In Japan and Korea, still as of the 2020s, a variation of ASCII is used, in which the backslash (5C hex) is rendered as ¥ (a Yen sign, in Japan) or ₩ (a Won sign, in Korea).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] This means that, for example, the file path C:\Users\Smith is shown as C:¥Users¥Smith (in Japan) or C:₩Users₩Smith (in Korea).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In Europe, teletext character sets, which are variants of ASCII, are used for broadcast TV subtitles, defined by World System Teletext and broadcast using the DVB-TXT standard for embedding teletext into DVB transmissions.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In the case that the subtitles were initially authored for teletext and converted, the derived subtitle formats are constrained to the same character sets.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Eventually, as 8-, 16-, and 32-bit (and later 64-bit) computers began to replace 12-, 18-, and 36-bit computers as the norm, it became common to use an 8-bit byte to store each character in memory, providing an opportunity for extended, 8-bit relatives of ASCII.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In most cases these developed as true extensions of ASCII, leaving the original character-mapping intact, but adding additional character definitions after the first 128 (i.e., 7-bit) characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ASCII itself remained a seven-bit code: the term "extended ASCII" has no official status.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] For some countries, 8-bit extensions of ASCII were developed that included support for characters used in local languages (for example, ISCII for India and VISCII for Vietnam).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Even for markets where it was not necessary to add many characters to support additional languages, manufacturers of early home computer systems often developed their own 8-bit extensions of ASCII to include additional characters, such as box-drawing characters, semigraphics, and video game sprites.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Often, these additions also replaced control characters (index 0 to 31, as well as index 127) with even more platform-specific extensions.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] In other cases, the extra bit was used for some other purpose, such as toggling inverse video; this approach was used by ATASCII, an extension of ASCII developed by Atari.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Most ASCII extensions are based on ASCII-1967 (the current standard), but some extensions are instead based on the earlier ASCII-1963.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] For example, PETSCII, which was developed by Commodore International for their 8-bit systems, is based on ASCII-1963.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Likewise, many Sharp MZ character sets are based on ASCII-1963.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] IBM defined code page 437 for the IBM PC, replacing the control characters with graphic symbols such as smiley faces, and mapping additional graphic characters to the upper 128 positions.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Digital Equipment Corporation developed the Multinational Character Set (DEC-MCS) for use in the popular VT220 terminal as one of the first extensions designed more for international languages than for block graphics.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Apple defined Mac OS Roman for the Macintosh and Adobe defined the PostScript Standard Encoding for PostScript; both sets contained "international" letters, typographic symbols and punctuation marks instead of graphics, more like modern character sets.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] The ISO/IEC 8859 standard (derived from the DEC-MCS) provided a standard that most systems copied (or at least were based on, when not copied exactly).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] A popular further extension designed by Microsoft, Windows-1252 (often mislabeled as ISO-8859-1), added the typographic punctuation marks needed for traditional text printing.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ISO-8859-1, Windows-1252, and the original 7-bit ASCII were the most common character encoding methods on the World Wide Web until 2008, when UTF-8 overtook them.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ISO/IEC 4873 introduced 32 additional control codes defined in the 80–9F hexadecimal range, as part of extending the 7-bit ASCII encoding to become an 8-bit system.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Unicode and the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set (UCS) have a much wider array of characters and their various encoding forms have begun to supplant ISO/IEC 8859 and ASCII rapidly in many environments.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] While ASCII is limited to 128 characters, Unicode and the UCS support more characters by separating the concepts of unique identification (using natural numbers called *code points*) and encoding (to 8-, 16-, or 32-bit binary formats, called UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, respectively).
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] ASCII was incorporated into the Unicode (1991) character set as the first 128 symbols, so the 7-bit ASCII characters have the same numeric codes in both sets.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] This allows UTF-8 to be backward compatible with 7-bit ASCII, as a UTF-8 file containing only ASCII characters is identical to an ASCII file containing the same sequence of characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/ascii] Even more importantly, forward compatibility is ensured as software that recognizes only 7-bit ASCII characters as special and does not alter bytes with the highest bit set (as is often done to support 8-bit ASCII extensions such as ISO-8859-1) will preserve UTF-8 data unchanged.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Early character encodings that originated with optical or electrical telegraphy and in early computers could only represent a subset of the characters used in languages, sometimes restricted to upper case letters, numerals and limited punctuation.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Over time, encodings capable of representing more characters were created, such as ASCII, ISO/IEC 8859, and Unicode encodings such as UTF-8 and UTF-16.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The most popular character encoding on the World Wide Web is UTF-8, which is used in 98.9% of surveyed web sites, as of January 2026.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] In application programs and operating system tasks, both UTF-8 and UTF-16 are popular options.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The history of character codes illustrates the evolving need for machine-mediated character-based symbolic information over a distance, using once-novel electrical means.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The earliest codes were based upon manual and hand-written encoding and cyphering systems, such as Bacon's cipher, Braille, international maritime signal flags, and the 4-digit encoding of Chinese characters for a Chinese telegraph code (Hans Schjellerup, 1869).
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] With the adoption of electrical and electro-mechanical techniques these earliest codes were adapted to the new capabilities and limitations of the early machines.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The earliest well-known electrically transmitted character code, Morse code, introduced in the 1840s, used a system of four "symbols" (short signal, long signal, short space, long space) to generate codes of variable length.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Though some commercial use of Morse code was via machinery, it was often used as a manual code, generated by hand on a telegraph key and decipherable by ear, and persists in amateur radio and aeronautical use.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Most codes are of fixed per-character length or variable-length sequences of fixed-length codes (e.g.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Common examples of character encoding systems include Morse code, the Baudot code, the American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII) and Unicode.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Unicode, a well-defined and extensible encoding system, has replaced most earlier character encodings, but the path of code development to the present is fairly well known.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The Baudot code, a five-bit encoding, was created by Émile Baudot in 1870, patented in 1874, modified by Donald Murray in 1901, and standardized by CCITT as International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The name *baudot* has been erroneously applied to ITA2 and its many variants.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] ITA2 suffered from many shortcomings and was often improved by many equipment manufacturers, sometimes creating compatibility issues.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Herman Hollerith invented punch card data encoding in the late 19th century to analyze census data.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Initially, each hole position represented a different data element, but later, numeric information was encoded by numbering the lower rows 0 to 9, with a punch in a column representing its row number.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Later alphabetic data was encoded by allowing more than one punch per column.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Electromechanical tabulating machines represented date internally by the timing of pulses relative to the motion of the cards through the machine.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] When IBM went to electronic processing, starting with the IBM 603 Electronic Multiplier, it used a variety of binary encoding schemes that were tied to the punch card code.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] IBM used several binary-coded decimal (BCD) six-bit character encoding schemes, starting as early as 1953 in its 702 and 704 computers, and in its later 7000 Series and 1400 series, as well as in associated peripherals.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Since the punched card code then in use was limited to digits, upper-case English letters and a few special characters, six bits were sufficient.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] These BCD encodings extended existing simple four-bit numeric encoding to include alphabetic and special characters, mapping them easily to punch-card encoding which was already in widespread use.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] IBM's codes were used primarily with IBM equipment.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Other computer vendors of the era had their own character codes, often six-bit, such as the encoding used by the UNIVAC I.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] They usually had the ability to read tapes produced on IBM equipment.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] IBM's BCD encodings were the precursors of their Extended Binary-Coded Decimal Interchange Code (usually abbreviated as EBCDIC), an eight-bit encoding scheme developed in 1963 for the IBM System/360 that featured a larger character set, including lower case letters.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] In 1959, the U.S. military defined its Fieldata code, a six-or seven-bit code, introduced by the U.S.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] While Fieldata addressed many of the then-modern issues (e.g. letter and digit codes arranged for machine collation), it fell short of its goals and was short-lived.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] In 1963 the first ASCII code was released (X3.4-1963) by the ASCII committee (which contained at least one member of the Fieldata committee, W.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Leubbert), which addressed most of the shortcomings of Fieldata, using a simpler seven-bit code.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Many of the changes were subtle, such as collatable character sets within certain numeric ranges.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] ASCII63 was a success, widely adopted by industry, and with the follow-up issue of the 1967 ASCII code (which added lower-case letters and fixed some "control code" issues) ASCII67 was adopted fairly widely.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] ASCII67's American-centric nature was somewhat addressed in the European ECMA-6 standard.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Eight-bit extended ASCII encodings, such as various vendor extensions and the ISO/IEC 8859 series, supported all ASCII characters as well as additional non-ASCII characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] In 1985, the average personal computer user's hard disk drive could store only about 10 megabytes, and it cost approximately US$250 on the wholesale market (and much higher if purchased separately at retail), so it was very important at the time to make every bit count.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The compromise solution that was eventually found and developed into Unicode was to break the assumption (dating back to telegraph codes) that each character should always directly correspond to a particular sequence of bits.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Instead, characters would first be mapped to a universal intermediate representation in the form of abstract numbers called code points.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Code points would then be represented in a variety of ways and with various default numbers of bits per character (code units) depending on context.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] To encode code points higher than the length of the code unit, such as above 256 for eight-bit units, the solution was to implement variable-length encodings where an escape sequence would signal that subsequent bits should be parsed as a higher code point.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The various terms related to character encoding are often used inconsistently or incorrectly.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Historically, the same standard would specify a repertoire of characters and how they were to be encoded into a stream of code units – usually with a single character per code unit.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] However, due to the emergence of more sophisticated character encodings, the distinction between terms has become important.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A character is the smallest unit of text that has semantic value.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] In linguistics, this is called a grapheme and each of the various ways it may be written are called glyphs.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] What constitutes a character varies between character encodings.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] For example, for letters with diacritics, there are two distinct approaches that can be taken to encode them.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] They can be encoded either as a single unified character (known as a precomposed character), or as separate characters that combine into a single glyph.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The former simplifies the text handling system, but the latter allows any letter/diacritic combination to be used in text.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Some writing systems, such as Arabic and Hebrew, have graphemes whose shape and joining depend on context.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A character set is a collection of characters used to represent text.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] For example, the Latin alphabet and Greek alphabet are character sets.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A coded character set is a character set with each item uniquely mapped to a numberic value.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] This is also known as a code page, although that term is generally antiquated.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Originally, *code page* referred to a page number in an IBM manual that defined a particular character encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Other vendors, including Microsoft, SAP, and Oracle Corporation, also published their own code pages, including notable Windows code page and code page 437.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Despite no longer referring to specific pages in a manual, many character encodings are still identified to by the same number.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Likewise, the term *code page* is still used to refer to character encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the term *charmap* is commonly used; usually in the larger context of locales.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] IBM's Character Data Representation Architecture (CDRA) designates each entity with a coded character set identifier (CCSID), which is variously called a *charset*, *character set*, *code page*, or *CHARMAP*.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A character repertoire is a set of characters that can be represented by a particular coded character set.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The repertoire may be closed, meaning that no additions are allowed without creating a new standard (as is the case with ASCII and most of the ISO-8859 series); or it may be open, allowing additions (as is the case with Unicode and to a limited extent Windows code pages).
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A code point is the value or position of a character in a coded character set.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A code point is represented by a sequence of code units.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Code space is the range of numerical values spanned by a coded character set.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A code unit is the minimum bit combination that can represent a character in a character encoding (in computer science terms, it is the word size of the character encoding).
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Common code units include 7-bit, 8-bit, 16-bit, and 32-bit.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] In some encodings, some characters are encoded as multiple code units.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Unicode and its parallel standard, the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set, together constitute a unified standard for character encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The purpose of this decomposition is to establish a universal set of characters that can be encoded in a variety of ways.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] To describe the model precisely, Unicode uses existing terms and defines new terms.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] An abstract character repertoire (ACR) is the full set of abstract characters that a system supports.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Unicode has an open repertoire, meaning that new characters will be added to the repertoire over time.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A coded character set (CCS) is a function that maps characters to *code points* (each code point represents one character).
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] For example, in a given repertoire, the capital letter "A" in the Latin alphabet might be represented by the code point 65, the character "B" by 66, and so on.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Multiple coded character sets may share the same character repertoire; for example ISO/IEC 8859-1 and IBM code pages 037 and 500 all cover the same repertoire but map them to different code points.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Hardware and software systems typically have a maximum "native" word length, such as 16 or 32 bits.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A character encoding may define code points whose length exceeds a system's native word length.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] *A character encoding form* (CEF) is the mapping of code points to *code units* that break up a code point in a standardized way so that each code unit fits within the system's word length.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] For example, a computer that represents numbers in 16-bit units can only represent code points up to 65,535 per unit, but larger code points can be represented using multiple 16-bit units as defined by the CEF.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A character encoding scheme (CES) is the mapping of code units to a sequence of octets to facilitate storage on an octet-based file system or transmission over an octet-based network.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] See comparison of Unicode encodings for a detailed discussion.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] There may be a higher-level protocol which supplies additional information to select the particular variant of a Unicode character, particularly where there are regional variants that have been 'unified' in Unicode as the same character.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] An example is the XML attribute xml:lang.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The Unicode model uses the term "character map" for other systems which directly assign a sequence of characters to a sequence of bytes, covering all of the CCS, CEF and CES layers.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] A character is commonly documented as 'U+' followed by its code point value in hexadecimal.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The range of valid code points (the code space) for the Unicode standard is U+0000 to U+10FFFF, inclusive, divided in 17 planes, identified by the numbers 0 to 16.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Characters in the range U+0000 to U+FFFF are in plane 0, called the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP).
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] This plane contains the most commonly used characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Characters in the range U+10000 to U+10FFFF in the other planes are called supplementary characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Consider, "ab̲c𐐀" – a string containing a Unicode combining character (U+0332 ◌̲ COMBINING LOW LINE to underline the ⟨b⟩) as well as a supplementary character (U+10400 𐐀 DESERET CAPITAL LETTER LONG I).
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Note in particular that 𐐀 is represented with either one 32-bit value (UTF-32), two 16-bit values (UTF-16), or four 8-bit values (UTF-8).
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] Although each of those forms uses the same total number of bits (32) to represent the grapheme, it is not obvious how the actual numeric byte values are related.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] To support environments using multiple character encodings, software has been developed to translate text between character encoding schemes, a process known as transcoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/character-encoding] The most used character encoding on the web is UTF-8, used in 98.9% of surveyed web sites, as of January 2026.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] In computing, **endianness** is the order in which bytes within a *word* data type are transmitted over a data communication medium or addressed in computer memory, counting only byte significance compared to earliness.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Endianness is primarily expressed as **big-endian** (**BE**) or **little-endian** (**LE**).
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Computers store information in various-sized groups of binary bits.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Each group is assigned a number, called its *address*, that the computer uses to access that data.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] On most modern computers, the smallest data group with an address is eight bits long, and is called a *byte*.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Larger groups comprise two or more bytes; for example, a *word* often contains 32 bits or 64 bits.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] There are two principal ways a computer could number the individual bytes in a larger group, starting at either end.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] A big-endian system stores the most significant byte of a word at the smallest memory address and the least significant byte at the largest.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] A little-endian system, in contrast, stores the least-significant byte at the smallest address.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Of the two, big-endian is thus closer to the way the digits of numbers are written left-to-right in English, with the most significant digit first, comparing digits to bytes and assuming addresses increase from left to right.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Both types of endianness are in widespread use in digital electronic engineering.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The initial choice of endianness of a new design is often arbitrary, but later technology revisions and updates perpetuate the existing endianness to maintain backward compatibility.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Big-endianness is the dominant ordering in networking protocols, such as in the Internet protocol suite, where it is referred to as *network order*, transmitting the most significant byte first.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Conversely, little-endianness is the dominant ordering for processor architectures (x86, most ARM implementations, base RISC-V implementations) and their associated memory.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] File formats can use either ordering; some formats use a mixture of both or contain an indicator of which ordering is used throughout the file.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Endianness is primarily expressed as **big-endian** (BE) or **little-endian** (LE), terms introduced by Danny Cohen in an Internet Experiment Note published in 1980.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Cohen borrowed the terms from an absurd episode in the satirical novel *Gulliver's Travels* by Jonathan Swift.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] In the imaginary land of Lilliput, scholars are fiercely divided by a never-ending debate over how correctly to break the shell of a boiled egg.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Those who insist on breaking the big end of the shell are Big-Endians, while their opponents who break the opposite end of the shell are Little-Endians.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Computer memory consists of a sequence of storage cells (smallest addressable units); in machines that support byte addressing, those units are called *bytes*.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Each byte is identified and accessed in hardware and software by its memory address.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] If the total number of bytes in memory is *n*, then addresses are enumerated from 0 to *n* − 1.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Computer programs often use data structures or fields that may consist of more data than can be stored in one byte.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] In the context of this article, where its type cannot be arbitrarily complicated, a *field* consists of a consecutive sequence of bytes and represents a *simple data value* which, at least potentially, can be manipulated by *one* single hardware instruction.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] On most systems, the address of a multi-byte simple data value is the address of its first byte (the byte with the lowest address).
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] There are exceptions to this rule – for example, the Add instruction of the IBM 1401 addresses variable-length fields at their low-order (highest-addressed) position with their lengths being defined by a word mark set at their high-order (lowest-addressed) position.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] When an operation such as addition is performed, the processor begins at the low-order positions at the high addresses of the two fields and works its way down to the high-order.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Another important attribute of a byte being part of a *field* is its *significance*.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] These attributes of the parts of a field play an important role in the sequence the bytes are accessed by the computer hardware, more precisely: by the low-level algorithms contributing to the results of a computer instruction.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Positional number systems (mostly base 2, or less often base 10) are the predominant way of representing and particularly of manipulating integer data by computers.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] In pure form, this is valid for moderately sized non-negative integers, e.g., of C data type `unsigned`.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] In such a number system, the *value* of a digit that contributes to the whole number is determined not only by its value as a single digit, but also by the position it holds in the complete number, called its significance.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] In *big-endian* and *little-endian*, the *end* is the extremity where the *big* or *little* significance is written in the location indexed by the lowest memory address.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] When character (text) strings are to be compared with one another, e.g., in order to support some mechanism like sorting, this is very frequently done lexicographically where a single positional element (character) also has a positional value.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Lexicographical comparison means almost everywhere: first character ranks highest, as in the telephone book.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Almost all machines that can do this using a single instruction are big-endian or at least mixed-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Integer numbers written as text are always represented most significant digit first in memory, which is similar to big-endian, independently of text direction.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] When memory bytes are printed sequentially from left to right (e.g., in a hex dump), little-endian representation of integers has the significance decreasing from right to left.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] In other words, it appears backwards when visualized, which can be counterintuitive.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] This behavior arises, for example, in FourCC or similar techniques that involve packing characters into an integer, so that it becomes a sequence of specific characters in memory.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] For example, take the string "JOHN", stored in hexadecimal ASCII.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] On big-endian machines, the value appears left-to-right, coinciding with the correct string order for reading the result ("J O H N").
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] But on a little-endian machine, one would see "N H O J".
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Middle-endian machines complicate this even further; for example, on the PDP-11, a 32-bit float is stored as two 16-bit words "JO" "HN" in big-endian, with the characters in the 16-bit words being stored in little-endian, resulting in "O J N H".
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Byte-swapping consists of rearranging bytes to change endianness.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Many compilers provide built-ins that are likely to be compiled into native processor instructions (`bswap`/`movbe`), such as `__builtin_bswap32`.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Some CPU instruction sets provide native support for endian byte swapping, such as `bswap` (x86 — 486 and later, i960 — i960Jx and later), and `rev` (ARMv6 and later).
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Some compilers have built-in facilities for byte swapping.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] For example, GNU Fortran and the Intel Fortran Compiler both support the non-standard `CONVERT` specifier when opening a file, e.g.: `OPEN(unit, CONVERT='BIG_ENDIAN',...)`.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Other compilers have options for generating code that globally enables the conversion for all file IO operations.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] This permits the reuse of code on a system with the opposite endianness without code modification.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] For example, a 32-bit memory location with content `4A 00 00 00` can be read at the same address as either 8-bit (value = 4A), 16-bit (004A), 24-bit (00004A), or 32-bit (0000004A), all of which retain the same numeric value.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Although this little-endian property is rarely used directly by high-level programmers, it is occasionally employed by code optimizers as well as by assembly language programmers.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] While not allowed by C++, such type punning code is allowed as "implementation-defined" by the C11 standard and commonly used in code interacting with hardware.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Some operations in positional number systems have a natural or preferred order in which the elementary steps are to be executed.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] This order may affect their performance on small-scale byte-addressable processors and microcontrollers.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] However, high-performance processors usually fetch multi-byte operands from memory in the same amount of time they would have fetched a single byte, so the complexity of the hardware is not affected by the byte ordering.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Addition, subtraction, and multiplication start at the least significant digit position and propagate the carry to the subsequent more significant position.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] On most systems, the address of a multi-byte value is the address of its first byte (the byte with the lowest address).
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The implementation of these operations is marginally simpler using little-endian machines, where this first byte contains the least significant digit.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Comparison and division start at the most significant digit and propagate a possible carry to the subsequent less significant digits.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] For fixed-length numerical values (typically of length 1,2,4,8,16), the implementation of these operations is marginally simpler on big-endian machines.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Some big-endian processors (e.g., the IBM System/360 and its successors) contain hardware instructions for lexicographically comparing varying-length character strings.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The normal data transport by an assignment statement is, in principle, independent of the endianness of the processor.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Many historical and extant processors use a big-endian memory representation, either exclusively or as a design option.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The IBM System/360 uses big-endian byte order, as do its successors System/370, ESA/390, and z/Architecture.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The PDP-10 uses big-endian addressing for byte-oriented instructions.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The IBM Series/1 minicomputer uses big-endian byte order.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The Motorola 6800 / 6801, the 6809 and the 68000 series of processors use the big-endian format.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Solely big-endian architectures include the IBM z/Architecture and OpenRISC.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The PDP-11 minicomputer, however, uses little-endian byte order, as does its VAX successor.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The Datapoint 2200 used simple bit-serial logic with little-endian to facilitate carry propagation.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] When Intel developed the 8008 microprocessor for Datapoint, they used little-endian for compatibility.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] However, as Intel was unable to deliver the 8008 in time, Datapoint used a medium-scale integration equivalent, but the little-endianness was retained in most Intel designs, including the MCS-48 and the 8086 and its x86 successors, including IA-32 and x86-64 processors.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The MOS Technology 6502 family (including Western Design Center 65802 and 65C816), the Zilog Z80 (including Z180 and eZ80), the Altera Nios II, the Atmel AVR, the Andes Technology NDS32, the Qualcomm Hexagon, and many other processors and processor families are also little-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The Intel 8051, unlike other Intel processors, expects 16-bit addresses for LJMP and LCALL in big-endian format; however, xCALL instructions store the return address onto the stack in little-endian format.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Some instruction set architectures feature a setting which allows for switchable endianness in data fetches and stores, instruction fetches, or both; those instruction set architectures are referred to as *bi-endian*.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Architectures that support switchable endianness include PowerPC/Power ISA, SPARC V9, ARM versions 3 and above, DEC Alpha, MIPS, Intel i860, PA-RISC, SuperH SH-4, IA-64, C-Sky, and RISC-V.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] This feature can improve performance or simplify the logic of networking devices and software.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The word *bi-endian*, when said of hardware, denotes the capability of the machine to compute or pass data in either endian format.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] IBM AIX and IBM i run in big-endian mode on bi-endian Power ISA; Linux originally ran in big-endian mode, but by 2019, IBM had transitioned to little-endian mode for Linux to ease the porting of Linux software from x86 to Power.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] SPARC has no relevant little-endian deployment, as both Oracle Solaris and Linux run in big-endian mode on bi-endian SPARC systems, and can be considered big-endian in practice.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] ARM, C-Sky, and RISC-V have no relevant big-endian deployments and can be considered little-endian in practice.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The term *bi-endian* refers primarily to how a processor treats data accesses.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Instruction accesses (fetches of instruction words) on a given processor may still assume a fixed endianness, even if data accesses are fully bi-endian, though this is not always the case, such as on Intel's IA-64-based Itanium CPU, which allows both.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Some nominally bi-endian CPUs require motherboard help to fully switch endianness.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] In the absence of this unusual motherboard hardware, device driver software must write to different addresses to undo the incomplete transformation and also must perform a normal byte swap.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Some CPUs, such as many PowerPC processors intended for embedded use and almost all SPARC processors, allow per-page choice of endianness.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] SPARC processors since the late 1990s (SPARC v9 compliant processors) allow data endianness to be chosen with each individual instruction that loads from or stores to memory.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The ARM architecture supports two big-endian modes, called *BE-8* and *BE-32*.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] CPUs up to ARMv5 only support BE-32 or word-invariant mode.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Here, any naturally aligned 32-bit access works like in little-endian mode, but access to a byte or 16-bit word is redirected to the corresponding address and unaligned access is not allowed.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] ARMv6 introduces BE-8 or byte-invariant mode, where access to a single byte works as in little-endian mode, but accessing a 16-bit, 32-bit or (starting with ARMv8) 64-bit word results in a byte swap of the data.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] This simplifies unaligned memory access as well as memory-mapped access to registers other than 32-bit.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Many processors have instructions to convert a word in a register to the opposite endianness, that is, they swap the order of the bytes in a 16-, 32- or 64-bit word.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Recent Intel x86 and x86-64 architecture CPUs have a MOVBE instruction (Intel Core since generation 4, after Atom), which fetches a big-endian format word from memory or writes a word into memory in big-endian format.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] These processors are otherwise thoroughly little-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] There are also devices that use different formats in different places.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] For instance, the BQ27421 Texas Instruments battery gauge uses the little-endian format for its registers and the big-endian format for its random-access memory.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] SPARC historically used big-endian until version 9, which is bi-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Similarly, early IBM POWER processors were big-endian, but the PowerPC and Power ISA descendants are now bi-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The ARM architecture was little-endian before version 3, when it became bi-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Although many processors use little-endian storage for all types of data (integer, floating point), there are a number of hardware architectures where floating-point numbers are represented in big-endian form while integers are represented in little-endian form.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] There are ARM processors that have mixed-endian floating-point representation for double-precision numbers: each of the two 32-bit words is stored as little-endian, but the most significant word is stored first.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] VAX floating point stores little-endian 16-bit words in big-endian order.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Because there have been many floating-point formats with no network standard representation for them, the XDR standard uses big-endian IEEE 754 as its representation.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] It may therefore appear strange that the widespread IEEE 754 floating-point standard does not specify endianness.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Theoretically, this means that even standard IEEE floating-point data written by one machine might not be readable by another.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] However, on modern standard computers (i.e., implementing IEEE 754), one may safely assume that the endianness is the same for floating-point numbers as for integers, making the conversion straightforward regardless of data type.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Small embedded systems using special floating-point formats may be another matter, however.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Most instructions considered so far contain the size (lengths) of their operands within the operation code.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Frequently available operand lengths are 1, 2, 4, 8, or 16 bytes.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] But there are also architectures where the length of an operand may be held in a separate field of the instruction or with the operand itself, e.g., by means of a word mark.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Such an approach allows operand lengths up to 256 bytes or larger.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The data types of such operands are character strings or BCD.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Machines able to manipulate such data with one instruction (e.g. compare, add) include the IBM 1401, 1410, 1620, System/360, System/370, ESA/390, and z/Architecture, all of them of type big-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Numerous other orderings, generically called *middle-endian* or *mixed-endian*, are possible.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The PDP-11 is primarily a 16-bit little-endian system.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The instructions to convert between floating-point and integer values in the optional floating-point processor of the PDP-11/45, PDP-11/70, and in some later processors, stored 32-bit *double precision integer long* values with the 16-bit halves swapped from the expected little-endian order.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The UNIX C compiler used the same format for 32-bit long integers.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] UNIX was one of the first systems to allow the same code to be compiled for platforms with different internal representations.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] One of the first programs converted was supposed to print out `Unix`, but on the Series/1 it printed `nUxi` instead.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Segment descriptors of IA-32 and compatible processors keep a 32-bit base address of the segment stored in little-endian order, but in four nonconsecutive bytes, at relative positions 2, 3, 4 and 7 of the descriptor start.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Hardware description languages (HDLs) used to express digital logic often support arbitrary endianness, with arbitrary granularity.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] For example, in SystemVerilog, a word can be defined as little-endian or big-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The recognition of endianness is important when reading a file or filesystem created on a computer with different endianness.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] An attempt to read such a file using Fortran on a system of the other endianness results in a run-time error, because the count fields are incorrect.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Unicode text can optionally start with a byte order mark (BOM) to signal the endianness of the file or stream.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] In UTF-32 for example, a big-endian file should start with `00 00 FE FF`; a little-endian should start with `FF FE 00 00`.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Application binary data formats, such as MATLAB *.mat* files, or the *.bil* data format, used in topography, are usually endianness-independent.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] This is achieved by storing the data always in one fixed endianness or carrying with the data a switch to indicate the endianness.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] An example of the former is the binary XLS file format that is portable between Windows and Mac systems and always little-endian, requiring the Mac application to swap the bytes on load and save when running on a big-endian Motorola 68K or PowerPC processor.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] TIFF image files are an example of the second strategy, whose header instructs the application about the endianness of their internal binary integers.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] If a file starts with the signature `MM` it means that integers are represented as big-endian, while `II` means little-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Those signatures need a single 16-bit word each, and they are palindromes, so they are endianness independent.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] `I` stands for Intel and `M` stands for Motorola.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Intel CPUs are little-endian, while Motorola 680x0 CPUs are big-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] This explicit signature allows a TIFF reader program to swap bytes if necessary when a given file was generated by a TIFF writer program running on a computer with a different endianness.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] ZFS, which combines a filesystem and a logical volume manager, is known to provide adaptive endianness and to work with both big-endian and little-endian systems.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Many IETF RFCs use the term *network order*, meaning the order of transmission for bytes *over the wire* in network protocols.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Among others, the historic RFC 1700 defines the network order for protocols in the Internet protocol suite to be big-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] However, not all protocols use big-endian byte order as the network order.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The Server Message Block (SMB) protocol uses little-endian byte order.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] In CANopen, multi-byte parameters are always sent least significant byte first (little-endian).
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] The same is true for Ethernet Powerlink.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] These functions may be a no-op on a big-endian system.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] While the high-level network protocols usually consider the byte (mostly meant as *octet*) as their atomic unit, the lowest layers of a network stack may deal with the ordering of bits within a byte.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Bit ordering is sometimes referred to as little-endian or big-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Bit ordering does not need to be the same as byte ordering.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] For example, RS-232 transmits bits least significant first, I2C transmits bits most significant first, and SPI can be sent in either order.
[src:encodings-serialization/endianness] Ethernet transmits individual bits least significant first, but bytes are sent big-endian.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Although it is known as *URL encoding*, it is also used more generally within the main Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) set, which includes both Uniform Resource Locator (URL) and Uniform Resource Name (URN).
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Consequently, it is also used in the preparation of data of the `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` media type, as is often used in the submission of HTML form data in HTTP requests.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] The characters allowed in a URI are either *reserved* or *unreserved* (or a percent character as part of a percent-encoding).
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] *Reserved* characters are those characters that sometimes have special meaning.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] For example, forward slash characters are used to separate different parts of a URL (or, more generally, a URI).
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] *Unreserved* characters have no such meanings.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Using percent-encoding, reserved characters are represented using special character sequences.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] The sets of reserved and unreserved characters and the circumstances under which certain reserved characters have special meaning have changed slightly with each revision of specifications that govern URIs and URI schemes.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Other characters in a URI must be percent-encoded.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] When a character from the reserved set (a "reserved character") has a special meaning (a "reserved purpose") in a certain context, and a URI scheme says that it is necessary to use that character for some *other* purpose, then the character must be *percent-encoded*.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Percent-encoding a reserved character involves converting the character to its corresponding byte value in ASCII and then representing that value as a pair of hexadecimal digits (if there is a single hex digit, a leading zero is added).
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] The digits, preceded by a percent sign (`%`) as an escape character, are then used in the URI in place of the reserved character.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] The reserved character `/`, for example, if used in the "path" component of a URI, has the special meaning of being a delimiter *between* path segments.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] If, according to a given URI scheme, `/` needs to be *in* a path segment, then the three characters `%2F` or `%2f` must be used in the segment instead of a raw `/`.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Reserved characters that have no reserved purpose in a particular context may also be percent-encoded but are not semantically different from those that are not.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] In the "query" component of a URI (the part after a `?` character), for example, `/` is still considered a reserved character but it normally has no reserved purpose, unless a particular URI scheme says otherwise.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] The character does not need to be percent-encoded when it has no reserved purpose.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] URIs that differ only by whether a reserved character is percent-encoded or appears literally are normally considered not equivalent (denoting the same resource) unless it can be determined that the reserved characters in question have no reserved purpose.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] This determination is dependent upon the rules established for reserved characters by individual URI schemes.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Characters from the unreserved set never need to be percent-encoded.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] URIs that differ only by whether an unreserved character is percent-encoded or appears literally are equivalent by definition, but URI processors, in practice, may not always recognize this equivalence.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] For example, URI consumers *should not* treat `%41` differently from `A` or `%7E` differently from `~`, but some do.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] For maximal interoperability, URI producers are discouraged from percent-encoding unreserved characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Because the percent character ( `%` ) serves to indicate percent-encoded octets, it must itself be percent-encoded as `%25` to be used as data within a URI.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Most URI schemes involve the representation of arbitrary data, such as an IP address or file system path, as components of a URI.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] URI scheme specifications should, but often do not, provide an explicit mapping between URI characters and all possible data values being represented by those characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Since the publication of RFC 1738 in 1994 it has been specified that schemes that provide for the representation of binary data in a URI must divide the data into 8-bit bytes and percent-encode each byte in the same manner as above.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Byte value 0x0F, for example, should be represented by `%0F`, but byte value 0x41 can be represented by `A`, or `%41`.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] The use of unencoded characters for alphanumeric and other unreserved characters is typically preferred, as it results in shorter URLs.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] The procedure for percent-encoding binary data has often been extrapolated, sometimes inappropriately or without being fully specified, to apply to character-based data.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] The need to represent characters outside the ASCII range, however, grew quickly, and URI schemes and protocols often failed to provide standard rules for preparing character data for inclusion in a URI.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Web applications consequently began using different multi-byte, stateful, and other non-ASCII-compatible encodings as the basis for percent-encoding, leading to ambiguities and difficulty interpreting URIs reliably.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] For example, many URI schemes and protocols based on RFCs 1738 and 2396 presume that the data characters will be converted to bytes according to some unspecified character encoding before being represented in a URI by unreserved characters or percent-encoded bytes.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] If the scheme does not allow the URI to provide a hint as to what encoding was used, or if the encoding conflicts with the use of ASCII to percent-encode reserved and unreserved characters, then the URI cannot be reliably interpreted.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Some schemes fail to account for encoding at all and instead just suggest that data characters map directly to URI characters, which leaves it up to implementations to decide whether and how to percent-encode data characters that are in neither the reserved nor unreserved sets.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Arbitrary character data is sometimes percent-encoded and used in non-URI situations, such as for password-obfuscation programs or other system-specific translation protocols.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] This suggestion was introduced in January 2005 with the publication of RFC 3986.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] URI schemes introduced before this date are not affected.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Not addressed by the current specification is what to do with encoded character data.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] For example, in computers, character data manifests in encoded form, at some level, and thus could be treated as either binary or character data when being mapped to URI characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] Presumably, it is up to the URI scheme specifications to account for this possibility and require one or the other, but in practice, few, if any, actually do.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] There exists a non-standard encoding for Unicode characters: `%u*xxxx*`, where *xxxx* is a UTF-16 code unit represented as four hexadecimal digits.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] For example, the 13th edition of ECMA-262 includes an `escape` function that uses this syntax.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] However, this behavior is not specified by any RFC, and has been rejected by the W3C.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] When data that has been entered into HTML forms is submitted, the form field names and values are encoded and sent to the server in an HTTP request message using method GET or POST, or, historically, via email.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] The encoding used by default is based on an early version of the general URI percent-encoding rules, with a number of modifications such as newline normalization and replacing spaces with `+` instead of `%20`.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] The media type of data encoded this way is `application/x-www-form-urlencoded`, and it is currently defined in the HTML and XForms specifications.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] In addition, the CGI specification contains rules for how web servers decode data of this type and make it available to applications.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] When HTML form data is sent in an HTTP GET request, it is included in the query component of the request URI using the same syntax described above.
[src:encodings-serialization/percent-encoding] When sent in an HTTP POST request or via email, the data is placed in the body of the message, and `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` is included in the message's Content-Type header.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Google developed Protocol Buffers for internal use and provided a code generator for multiple languages under an open-source license.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] The design goals for Protocol Buffers emphasized simplicity and performance.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] In particular, it was designed to be smaller and faster than XML.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is widely used at Google for storing and interchanging all kinds of structured information.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] The method serves as a basis for a custom remote procedure call (RPC) system that is used for nearly all inter-machine communication at Google.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is similar to the Apache Thrift, Amazon Ion, and Microsoft Bond protocols, offering a concrete RPC protocol stack to use for defined services called gRPC.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Data structure schemas (called *messages*) and services are described in a proto definition file (`.proto`) and compiled with `protoc`.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] This compilation generates code that can be invoked by a sender or recipient of these data structures.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] For example, `example.pb.cc` and `example.pb.h` are generated from `example.proto`.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] They define C++ classes for each message and service in `example.proto`.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Canonically, messages are serialized into a binary wire format which is compact, forward- and backward-compatible, but not self-describing (that is, there is no way to tell the names, meaning, or full datatypes of fields without an external specification).
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] There is no defined way to include or refer to such an external specification (schema) within a Protocol Buffers file.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] The officially supported implementation includes an ASCII serialization format, but this format—though self-describing—loses the forward- and backward-compatibility behavior, and is thus not a good choice for applications other than human editing and debugging.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Though the primary purpose of Protocol Buffers is to facilitate network communication, its simplicity and speed make Protocol Buffers an alternative to data-centric C++ classes and structs, especially where interoperability with other languages or systems might be needed in the future.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] The format is best suited for small data chunks that don't exceed a few megabytes and can be loaded/sent into memory right away and therefore is not a streamable format.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] The library doesn't provide compression out of the box.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] The format also isn't well supported in non–object-oriented languages (e.g.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] A schema for a particular use of protocol buffers associates data types with field names, using integers to identify each field.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] The `Point` message defines two mandatory data items, `x` and `y`.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] The tag is defined after the equal sign.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] The `Line` and `Polyline` messages, which both use `Point`, demonstrate how composition works in Protocol Buffers.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] `Polyline` has a `repeated` field, and thus `Polyline` behaves like a set of points (of unspecified number).
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] This schema can subsequently be compiled for use by one or more programming languages.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Google provides a compiler called `protoc` which can produce output for C++, Java or Python.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Other schema compilers are available from other sources to create language-dependent output for over 20 other languages.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 2.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java, C#, and Python.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 3.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java (including JavaNano, a dialect intended for low-resource environments), Kotlin, Python, Go, Ruby, Objective-C, C#, PHP, Dart.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] It also supports JavaScript since 3.0.0-beta-2.
[src:encodings-serialization/protocol-buffers] Third-party implementations are also available for Ada, Ballerina, C, C++, Dart, Elixir, Erlang, Haskell, JavaScript, Julia, Nim, Perl, PHP, Prolog, R, Rust, Scala, and Swift.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] While the Domain Name System (DNS) technically supports arbitrary sequences of octets in domain name labels, the DNS standards recommend the use of the LDH subset of ASCII conventionally used for host names, and require that string comparisons between DNS domain names should be case-insensitive.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] The Punycode syntax is a method of encoding strings containing Unicode characters, such as internationalized domain names (IDNA), into the LDH subset of ASCII favored by DNS.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] It is specified in IETF Request for Comments 3492.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] This section demonstrates the procedure for Punycode encoding, using as an example the German string "bücher" (English: *books*), which is translated into the label "bcher-kva".
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] To make the encoding and decoding algorithms simple, no attempt has been made to prevent some encoded values from encoding inadmissible Unicode values: however, these should be checked for and detected during decoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] Punycode is designed to work across all scripts, and to be self-optimizing by attempting to adapt to the character set ranges within the string as it operates.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] It is optimized for the case where the string is composed of zero or more ASCII characters and in addition characters from only one other script system, but will cope with any arbitrary Unicode string.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] Note that for DNS use, the domain name string is assumed to have been normalized using nameprep and (for top-level domains) filtered against an officially registered language table before being punycoded, and that the DNS protocol sets limits on the acceptable lengths of the output Punycode string.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] First, all ASCII characters in the string are copied from input to output, skipping over any other characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] For example, "bücher" is copied to "bcher".
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] If any characters were copied, i.e. if there was at least one ASCII character in the input, an ASCII hyphen is appended to the output (e.g., "bücher" → "bcher-", but "ü" → "").
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] Note that hyphens are themselves ASCII characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] Thus, they can be present in the input and, if so, they will be copied to the output.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] This causes no ambiguity: if the output contains hyphens, the one that got added is always the last one.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] It marks the end of the ASCII characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] The non-ASCII characters are sorted by Unicode value, lowest first (if a character occurs more than once, they are sorted by position).
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] Each is then encoded as a single number.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] This single number defines both the location to insert the character at and which character to insert.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] The encoded number is *insertionPoints* × *reducedCodepoint* + *index*.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] By dividing by insertionPoints and also getting the remainder, a decoder can determine reducedCodepoint and index.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] There are 6 possible insertion points for a character in the string "bcher" (including before the first character and after the last one). ü is Unicode code point 0xFC or 252 (see Latin-1 Supplement), and the reduced code point is 252 − 128, or 124.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] The ü is inserted at position 1, after the b.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] Thus the encoder will add the number 6 × 124 + 1 = 745, and the decoder can retrieve these by ⌊745 / 6⌋ = 124 and 745 mod 6 = 1.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] For the second and subsequent inserted characters, the difference between the number and the previous one is written.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] The number is encoded using the letters a through z and the digits 0 through 9.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] It is not base-36 but a more complex scheme, generalized variable-length integers, which allows the numbers to be concatenated with nothing separating them.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] To decode this string of symbols, a sequence of thresholds will be needed, in this case it is (1, 1, 26, 26, ...).
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] The weight (or place value) of the least-significant digit is always 1: 'k' (=10) with a weight of 1 equals 10.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] After this, the weight of the next digit depends on the first threshold: generally, for any *n*, the weight of the (*n*+1)-th digit is *w* × (36 − *t*), where *w* is the previous weight and *t* is the threshold of the *n*-th digit.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] So in this case, the second symbol has a place value of 36 minus the previous threshold value of 1, which equals 35.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] Since the second symbol is not less than its threshold value of 1, there is more to come.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] However, since the third symbol in this example is 'a' (=0), we may ignore calculating its weight.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] Number 745 will be encoded as 10 + 21 × 35 + 0 (base 35 used for second digit, the most significant digit 0 needed as terminator), 10 → 'k', 21 → 'v', 0 → 'a', so "bücher" → "bcher-kva".
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] The thresholds themselves are determined for each successive encoded character by an algorithm keeping them between 1 and 26 inclusive.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] The case can then be used to provide information about the original case of the string.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] Because special characters are sorted by their code points by encoding algorithm, for the insertion of a second special character in "bücher", the first possibility is "büücher" with code "bcher-kvaa", the second "bücüher" with code "bcher-kvab", etc.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] After "bücherü" with code "bcher-kvae" comes codes representing insertion of ý, the Unicode character following ü, starting with "ýbücher" with code "bcher-kvaf" (different from "übücher" coded "bcher-jvab"), etc.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] To prevent hyphens in non-international domain names from triggering a Punycode decoding, the string `xn--` is prepended to Punycode sequences in internationalized domain names.
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] This is called ACE (ASCII Compatible Encoding).
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] Thus the domain name "bücher.tld" would be represented in a URL as "xn--bcher-kva.tld".
[src:encodings-serialization/punycode] The following table shows examples of Punycode encodings for different types of input.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:encodings-serialization/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode has largely supplanted the previous environment of myriad incompatible character sets used within different locales and on different computer architectures.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The entire repertoire of these sets, plus many additional characters, were merged into the single Unicode set.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode is used to encode the vast majority of text on the Internet, including most web pages, and relevant Unicode support has become a common consideration in contemporary software development.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode is ultimately capable of encoding more than 1.1 million characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The Unicode character repertoire is synchronized with ISO/IEC 10646, each being code-for-code identical with one another.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] However, *The Unicode Standard* is more than just a repertoire within which characters are assigned.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] To aid developers and designers, the standard also provides charts and reference data, as well as annexes explaining concepts germane to various scripts, providing guidance for their implementation.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Topics covered by these annexes include character normalization, character composition and decomposition, collation, and directionality.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode encodes 3,790 emoji, with the continued development thereof conducted by the Consortium as a part of the standard.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The widespread adoption of Unicode was in large part responsible for the initial popularization of emoji outside of Japan.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode text is processed and stored as binary data using one of several encodings, which define how to translate the standard's abstracted codes for characters into sequences of bytes.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] *The Unicode Standard* itself defines three encodings: UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, though several others exist.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] UTF-8 is the most widely used by a large margin, in part due to its backwards-compatibility with ASCII.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode was originally designed with the intent of transcending limitations present in all text encodings designed up to that point: each encoding was relied upon for use in its own context, but with no particular expectation of compatibility with any other.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Indeed, any two encodings chosen were often totally unworkable when used together, with text encoded in one interpreted as garbage characters by the other.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Most encodings had only been designed to facilitate interoperation between a handful of scripts—often primarily between a given script and Latin characters—not between a large number of scripts, and not with all of the scripts supported being treated in a consistent manner.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The philosophy that underpins Unicode seeks to encode the underlying characters—graphemes and grapheme-like units—rather than graphical distinctions considered mere variant glyphs thereof, that are instead best handled by the typeface, through the use of markup, or by some other means.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In particularly complex cases, such as the treatment of orthographical variants in Han characters, there is considerable disagreement regarding which differences justify their own encodings, and which are only graphical variants of other characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] At the most abstract level, Unicode assigns a unique number called a *code point* to each character.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Many issues of visual representation—including size, shape, and style—are intended to be up to the discretion of the software actually rendering the text, such as a web browser or word processor.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] However, partially with the intent of encouraging rapid adoption, the simplicity of this original model has become somewhat more elaborate over time, and various pragmatic concessions have been made over the course of the standard's development.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The first 256 code points mirror the ISO/IEC 8859-1 standard, with the intent of trivializing the conversion of text already written in Western European scripts.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] To preserve the distinctions made by different legacy encodings, therefore allowing for conversion between them and Unicode without any loss of information, many characters nearly identical to others, in both appearance and intended function, were given distinct code points.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] For example, the Halfwidth and Fullwidth Forms block encompasses a full semantic duplicate of the Latin alphabet, because legacy CJK encodings contained both "fullwidth" (matching the width of CJK characters) and "halfwidth" (matching ordinary Latin script) characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The origins of Unicode can be traced back to the 1980s, to a group of individuals with connections to Xerox's Character Code Standard (XCCS).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In 1987, Xerox employee Joe Becker, along with Apple employees Lee Collins and Mark Davis, started investigating the practicalities of creating a universal character set.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] With additional input from Peter Fenwick and Dave Opstad, Becker published a draft proposal for an "international/multilingual text character encoding system in August 1988, tentatively called Unicode".
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] He explained that "the name 'Unicode' is intended to suggest a unique, unified, universal encoding".
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In early 1989, the Unicode working group expanded to include Ken Whistler and Mike Kernaghan of Metaphor, Karen Smith-Yoshimura and Joan Aliprand of Research Libraries Group, and Glenn Wright of Sun Microsystems.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The Research Libraries Group had an existing solution for East Asian character sets, which became one of the inputs to the Unicode character set.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In 1990, Michel Suignard and Asmus Freytag of Microsoft and NeXT's Rick McGowan had also joined the group.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] By the end of 1990, most of the work of remapping existing standards had been completed, and a final review draft of Unicode was ready.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The Unicode Consortium was incorporated in California on 3 January 1991, and the first volume of *The Unicode Standard* was published that October.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The second volume, now adding Han ideographs, was published in June 1992.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In 1996, a surrogate character mechanism was implemented in Unicode 2.0, so that Unicode was no longer restricted to 16 bits.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] This increased the Unicode codespace to over a million code points, which allowed for the encoding of many historic scripts, such as Egyptian hieroglyphs, and thousands of rarely used or obsolete characters that had not been anticipated for inclusion in the standard.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Among these characters are various rarely used CJK characters—many mainly being used in proper names, making them far more necessary for a universal encoding than the original Unicode architecture envisioned.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The Unicode Consortium is a non-profit organization that coordinates Unicode's development.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Full members include most of the main computer software and hardware companies (and few others) with any interest in text-processing standards, including Adobe, Apple, Google, IBM, Meta (previously as Facebook), Microsoft, Netflix, and SAP.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Over the years several countries or government agencies have been members of the Unicode Consortium.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The Consortium has the ambitious goal of eventually replacing existing character encoding schemes with Unicode and its standard Unicode Transformation Format (UTF) schemes, as many of the existing schemes are limited in size and scope and are incompatible with multilingual environments.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The **Unicode Bulldog Award** is given to people deemed to be influential in Unicode's development, with recipients including Tatsuo Kobayashi, Thomas Milo, Roozbeh Pournader, Ken Lunde, and Michael Everson.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] As of September 2025, a total of 172 scripts (alphabets, abugidas and syllabaries) are included in Unicode, covering most major writing systems in use today.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] There are still scripts that are not yet encoded, particularly those mainly used in historical, liturgical, and academic contexts.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Further additions of characters to the already encoded scripts, as well as symbols, in particular for mathematics and music also occur.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The Unicode Roadmap Committee (Michael Everson, Rick McGowan, Ken Whistler, V.S.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Umamaheswaran) maintain the list of scripts that are candidates or potential candidates for encoding and their tentative code block assignments on the Unicode Roadmap page of the Unicode Consortium website.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] For some scripts on the Roadmap, such as Jurchen and Khitan large script, encoding proposals have been made and they are working their way through the approval process.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] For other scripts, such as Numidian and Rongorongo, no proposal has yet been made, and they await agreement on character repertoire and other details from the user communities involved.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] There is also a Medieval Unicode Font Initiative focused on special Latin medieval characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Part of these proposals has been already included in Unicode.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The Script Encoding Initiative (SEI), a project created by Deborah Anderson at the University of California, Berkeley, was founded in 2002 with the goal of funding proposals for scripts not yet encoded in the standard.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Now run by Anushah Hossain, SEI has become a major source of proposed additions to the standard in recent years.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Although SEI collaborates with the Unicode Consortium and the ISO/IEC 10646 standards process, it operates independently, supporting the technical, linguistic, and historical research needed to prepare formal proposals.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] SEI maintains a database of scripts that have yet to be encoded in the Unicode Standard on the project's website.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The Unicode Consortium together with the ISO have developed a shared repertoire following the initial publication of *The Unicode Standard*: Unicode and the ISO's Universal Coded Character Set (UCS) use identical character names and code points.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] However, the Unicode versions do differ from their ISO equivalents in two significant ways.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] While the UCS is a simple character map, Unicode specifies the rules, algorithms, and properties necessary to achieve interoperability between different platforms and languages.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Thus, *The Unicode Standard* includes more information, covering in-depth topics such as bitwise encoding, collation, and rendering.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] It also provides a comprehensive catalog of character properties, including those needed for supporting bidirectional text, as well as visual charts and reference data sets to aid implementers.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Previously, *The Unicode Standard* was sold as a print volume containing the complete core specification, standard annexes, and code charts.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] However, version 5.0, published in 2006, was the last version printed this way.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Starting with version 5.2, only the core specification, published as a print-on-demand paperback, may be purchased.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The full text, on the other hand, is published as a free PDF on the Unicode website.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] A practical reason for this publication method highlights the second significant difference between the UCS and Unicode—the frequency with which updated versions are released and new characters added.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] *The Unicode Standard* has regularly released annual expanded versions, occasionally with more than one version released in a calendar year and with rare cases where the scheduled release had to be postponed.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] For instance, in April 2020, a month after version 13.0 was published, the Unicode Consortium announced they had changed the intended release date for version 14.0, pushing it back six months to September 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Thus far, the following versions of *The Unicode Standard* have been published.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Update versions, which do not include any changes to character repertoire, are signified by the third number (e.g., "version 4.0.1") and are omitted in the table below.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The total number of graphic and format characters, excluding private use characters, control characters, noncharacters, and surrogate code points).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] 2.0 added Amendments 5, 6, and 72.1 added two characters from Amendment 18.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Plus Amendment 1, as well as the Lari sign, nine CJK unified ideographs, and 41 emoji; 9.0 added Amendment 2, as well as Adlam, Newa, Japanese TV symbols, and 74 emoji and symbols.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Plus 56 emoji, 285 hentaigana characters, and 3 Zanabazar Square characters11.0 added 46 Mtavruli Georgian capital letters, 5 CJK unified ideographs, and 66 emoji12.0 added 62 additional characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In this normative notation, the two-character prefix `U+` always precedes a written code point, and the code points themselves are written as hexadecimal numbers.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] At least four hexadecimal digits are always written, with leading zeros prepended as needed.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] For example, the code point U+00F7 ÷ DIVISION SIGN is padded with two leading zeros, but U+13254 𓉔 EGYPTIAN HIEROGLYPH O004 () is not padded.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] There are a total of 1112064 valid code points within the codespace.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The Unicode codespace is divided into 17 *planes*, numbered 0 to 16.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Plane 0 is the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP), and contains the most commonly used characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] All code points in the BMP are accessed as a single code unit in UTF-16 encoding and can be encoded in one, two or three bytes in UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Code points in planes 1 through 16 (the *supplementary planes*) are accessed as surrogate pairs in UTF-16 and encoded in four bytes in UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Within each plane, characters are allocated within named *blocks* of related characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The size of a block is always a multiple of 16, and is often a multiple of 128, but is otherwise arbitrary.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Characters required for a given script may be spread out over several different, potentially disjunct blocks within the codespace.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Each code point is assigned a classification, listed as the code point's General Category property.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Here, at the uppermost level code points are categorized as one of Letter, Mark, Number, Punctuation, Symbol, Separator, or Other.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Under each category, each code point is then further subcategorized.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In most cases, other properties must be used to adequately describe all the characteristics of any given code point.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The 1024 points in the range U+D800–U+DBFF are known as *high-surrogate* code points, and code points in the range U+DC00–U+DFFF (1024 code points) are known as *low-surrogate* code points.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] A high-surrogate code point followed by a low-surrogate code point forms a *surrogate pair* in UTF-16 in order to represent code points greater than U+FFFF.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In principle, these code points cannot otherwise be used, though in practice this rule is often ignored, especially when not using UTF-16.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] A small set of code points are guaranteed never to be assigned to characters, although third-parties may make independent use of them at their discretion.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] There are 66 of these *noncharacters*: U+FDD0–U+FDEF and the last two code points in each of the 17 planes (e.g.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The set of noncharacters is stable, and no new noncharacters will ever be defined.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Like surrogates, the rule that these cannot be used is often ignored, although the operation of the byte order mark assumes that U+FFFE will never be the first code point in a text.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The exclusion of surrogates and noncharacters leaves 1111998 code points available for use.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] 65 code points, the ranges U+0000–U+001F and U+007F–U+009F, are reserved as *control codes*, corresponding to the C0 and C1 control codes as defined in ISO/IEC 6429.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] U+0009 TAB, U+000A LINE FEED, and U+000D CARRIAGE RETURN are widely used in texts using Unicode.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In a phenomenon known as mojibake, the C1 code points are improperly decoded according to the Windows-1252 codepage, previously widely used in Western European contexts.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Together, graphic, format, control code, and private use characters are collectively referred to as *assigned characters*.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] *Reserved* code points are those code points that are valid and available for use, but have not yet been assigned.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] As of Unicode 17.0, there are 814664 reserved code points.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The set of graphic and format characters defined by Unicode does not correspond directly to the repertoire of *abstract characters* representable under Unicode.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode encodes characters by associating an abstract character with a particular code point.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] However, not all abstract characters are encoded as a single Unicode character, and some abstract characters may be represented in Unicode by a sequence of two or more characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] For example, a Latin small letter "i" with an ogonek, a dot above, and an acute accent, which is required in Lithuanian, is represented by the character sequence U+012F; U+0307; U+0301.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode maintains a list of uniquely named character sequences for abstract characters that are not directly encoded in Unicode.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] All assigned characters have a unique and immutable name by which they are identified.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] This immutability has been guaranteed since version 2.0 of *The Unicode Standard* by its Name Stability policy.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In cases where a name is seriously defective and misleading, or has a serious typographical error, a formal **alias** may be defined that applications are encouraged to use in place of the official character name.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] For example, U+A015 ꀕ YI SYLLABLE WU has the formal alias YI SYLLABLE ITERATION MARK, and U+FE18 ︘ PRESENTATION FORM FOR VERTICAL RIGHT WHITE LENTICULAR BRAKCET (sic) has the formal alias PRESENTATION FORM FOR VERTICAL RIGHT WHITE LENTICULAR BRA**CK**ET.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode includes a mechanism for modifying characters that greatly extends the supported repertoire of glyphs.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] This covers the use of combining diacritical marks that may be added after the base character by the user.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Multiple combining diacritics may be simultaneously applied to the same character.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode also contains precomposed versions of most letter/diacritic combinations in normal use.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] These make the conversion to and from legacy encodings simpler, and allow applications to use Unicode as an internal text format without having to implement combining characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] For example, `é` can be represented in Unicode as U+0065 e LATIN SMALL LETTER E followed by U+0301 ◌́ COMBINING ACUTE ACCENT, and equivalently as the precomposed character U+00E9 é LATIN SMALL LETTER E WITH ACUTE.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Thus, users often have multiple equivalent ways of encoding the same character.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The mechanism of canonical equivalence within *The Unicode Standard* ensures the practical interchangeability of these equivalent encodings.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] An example of this arises with the Korean alphabet Hangul: Unicode provides a mechanism for composing Hangul syllables from their individual Hangul Jamo subcomponents.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] However, it also provides 11172 combinations of precomposed syllables made from the most common jamo.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] CJK characters presently only have codes for uncomposable radicals and precomposed forms.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Most Han characters have either been intentionally composed from, or reconstructed as compositions of, simpler orthographic elements called radicals, so in principle Unicode could have enabled their composition as it did with Hangul.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] While this could have greatly reduced the number of required code points, as well as allowing the algorithmic synthesis of many arbitrary new characters, the complexities of character etymologies and the post-hoc nature of radical systems add immense complexity to the proposal.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Indeed, attempts to design CJK encodings on the basis of composing radicals have been met with difficulties resulting from the reality that Chinese characters do not decompose as simply or as regularly as Hangul does.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The CJK Radicals Supplement block is assigned to the range U+2E80–U+2EFF, and the Kangxi radicals are assigned to U+2F00–U+2FDF.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Many scripts, including Arabic and Devanāgarī, have special orthographic rules that require certain combinations of letterforms to be combined into special ligature forms.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Instructions are also embedded in fonts to tell the operating system how to properly output different character sequences.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] A simple solution to the placement of combining marks or diacritics is assigning the marks a width of zero and placing the glyph itself to the left or right of the left sidebearing (depending on the direction of the script they are intended to be used with).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] A mark handled this way will appear over whatever character precedes it, but will not adjust its position relative to the width or height of the base glyph; it may be visually awkward and it may overlap some glyphs.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Real stacking is impossible but can be approximated in limited cases (for example, Thai top-combining vowels and tone marks can just be at different heights to start with).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Generally, this approach is only effective in monospaced fonts but may be used as a fallback rendering method when more complex methods fail.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Several subsets of Unicode are standardized: Microsoft Windows since Windows NT 4.0 supports WGL-4 with 657 characters, which is considered to support all contemporary European languages using the Latin, Greek, or Cyrillic script.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Other standardized subsets of Unicode include the Multilingual European Subsets: MES-1 (Latin scripts only; 335 characters), MES-2 (Latin, Greek, and Cyrillic; 1062 characters) and MES-3A & MES-3B (two larger subsets, not shown here).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] MES-2 includes every character in MES-1 and WGL-4.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The standard DIN 91379 specifies a subset of Unicode letters, special characters, and sequences of letters and diacritic signs to allow the correct representation of names and to simplify data exchange in Europe.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] This standard supports all of the official languages of all European Union countries, as well as the German minority languages and the official languages of Iceland, Liechtenstein, Norway, and Switzerland.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] To allow the transliteration of names in other writing systems to the Latin script according to the relevant ISO standards, all necessary combinations of base letters and diacritic signs are provided.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Rendering software that cannot process a Unicode character appropriately often displays it as an open rectangle, or as U+FFFD to indicate the position of the unrecognized character.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Some systems have made attempts to provide more information about such characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Apple's Last Resort font will display a substitute glyph indicating the Unicode range of the character, and the SIL International's Unicode fallback font will display a box showing the hexadecimal scalar value of the character.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Several mechanisms have been specified for storing a series of code points as a series of bytes.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Unicode defines two mapping methods: the **Unicode Transformation Format** (UTF) encodings, and the **Universal Coded Character Set** (UCS) encodings.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] An encoding maps (possibly a subset of) the range of Unicode *code points* to sequences of values in some fixed-size range, termed *code units*.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] All UTF encodings map code points to a unique sequence of bytes.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The numbers in the names of the encodings indicate the number of bits per code unit (for UTF encodings) or the number of bytes per code unit (for UCS encodings and UTF-1).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] UTF-8 and UTF-16 are the most commonly used encodings.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] UCS-2 is an obsolete subset of UTF-16; UCS-4 and UTF-32 are functionally equivalent.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] UTF-8 uses one to four 8-bit units (*bytes*) per code point and, being compact for Latin scripts and ASCII-compatible, provides the de facto standard encoding for the interchange of Unicode text.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] It is used by FreeBSD and most recent Linux distributions as a direct replacement for legacy encodings in general text handling.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The UCS-2 and UTF-16 encodings specify the Unicode byte order mark (BOM) for use at the beginnings of text files, which may be used for byte-order detection (or byte endianness detection).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The same character converted to UTF-8 becomes the byte sequence `EF BB BF`.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] *The Unicode Standard* allows the BOM "can serve as a signature for UTF-8 encoded text where the character set is unmarked".
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Some software developers have adopted it for other encodings, including UTF-8, in an attempt to distinguish UTF-8 from local 8-bit code pages.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] However RFC 3629, the UTF-8 standard, recommends that byte order marks be forbidden in protocols using UTF-8, but discusses the cases where this may not be possible.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In addition, the large restriction on possible patterns in UTF-8 (for instance there cannot be any lone bytes with the high bit set) means that it should be possible to distinguish UTF-8 from other character encodings without relying on the BOM.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In UTF-32 and UCS-4, one 32-bit code unit serves as a fairly direct representation of any character's code point (although the endianness, which varies across different platforms, affects how the code unit manifests as a byte sequence).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] In the other encodings, each code point may be represented by a variable number of code units.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] UTF-32 is widely used as an internal representation of text in programs (as opposed to stored or transmitted text), since every Unix operating system that uses the GCC compilers to generate software uses it as the standard "wide character" encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Recent versions of the Python programming language (beginning with 2.2) may also be configured to use UTF-32 as the representation for Unicode strings, effectively disseminating such encoding in high-level coded software.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Punycode, another encoding form, enables the encoding of Unicode strings into the limited character set supported by the ASCII-based Domain Name System (DNS).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The encoding is used as part of IDNA, which is a system enabling the use of Internationalized Domain Names in all scripts that are supported by Unicode.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] Earlier and now historical proposals include UTF-5 and UTF-6.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] GB18030 is another encoding form for Unicode, from the Standardization Administration of China.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] It is the official character set of the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] BOCU-1 and SCSU are Unicode compression schemes.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p01] The April Fools' Day RFC of 2005 specified two parody UTF encodings, UTF-9 and UTF-18.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Unicode, in the form of UTF-8, has been the most common encoding for the World Wide Web since 2008.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] It has near-universal adoption, and much of the non-UTF-8 content is found in other Unicode encodings, e.g.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] As of 2024, UTF-8 accounts for on average 98.3% of all web pages (and 983 of the top 1,000 highest-ranked web pages).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Although many pages only use ASCII characters to display content, UTF-8 was designed with 8-bit ASCII as a subset and almost no websites now declare their encoding to only be ASCII instead of UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Over a third of the languages tracked have 100% UTF-8 use.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] All internet protocols maintained by Internet Engineering Task Force, e.g.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] File Transfer Protocol (FTP), have required support for UTF-8 since the publication of RFC 2277 in 1998, which specified that all IETF protocols "MUST be able to use the UTF-8 charset".
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Unicode has become the dominant scheme for the internal processing and storage of text.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Although a great deal of text is still stored in legacy encodings, Unicode is used almost exclusively for building new information processing systems.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Early adopters tended to use UCS-2 (the fixed-length two-byte obsolete precursor to UTF-16) and later moved to UTF-16 (the variable-length current standard), as this was the least disruptive way to add support for non-BMP characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The best known such system is Windows NT (and its descendants, 2000, XP, Vista, 7, 8, 10, and 11), which uses UTF-16 as the sole internal character encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The Java and .NET bytecode environments, macOS, and KDE also use it for internal representation.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Partial support for Unicode can be installed on Windows 9x through the Microsoft Layer for Unicode.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] UTF-8 (originally developed for Plan 9) has become the main storage encoding on most Unix-like operating systems (though others are also used by some libraries) because it is a relatively easy replacement for traditional extended ASCII character sets.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] UTF-8 is also the most common Unicode encoding used in HTML documents on the World Wide Web.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Multilingual text-rendering engines which use Unicode include Uniscribe and DirectWrite for Microsoft Windows, ATSUI and Core Text for macOS, and Pango for GTK+ and the GNOME desktop.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Because keyboard layouts cannot have simple key combinations for all characters, several operating systems provide alternative input methods that allow access to the entire repertoire.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] ISO/IEC 14755, which standardises methods for entering Unicode characters from their code points, specifies several methods.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] There is the *Basic method*, where a *beginning sequence* is followed by the hexadecimal representation of the code point and the *ending sequence*.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] There is also a *screen-selection entry method* specified, where the characters are listed in a table on a screen, such as with a character map program.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Online tools for finding the code point for a known character include Unicode Lookup by Jonathan Hedley and Shapecatcher by Benjamin Milde.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] In Unicode Lookup, one enters a search key (e.g.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] "fractions"), and a list of corresponding characters with their code points is returned.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] In Shapecatcher, based on Shape context, one draws the character in a box and a list of characters approximating the drawing, with their code points, is returned.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] MIME defines two different mechanisms for encoding non-ASCII characters in email, depending on whether the characters are in email headers (such as the "Subject:"), or in the text body of the message; in both cases, the original character set is identified as well as a transfer encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] For email transmission of Unicode, the UTF-8 character set and the Base64 or the Quoted-printable transfer encoding are recommended, depending on whether much of the message consists of ASCII characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The details of the two different mechanisms are specified in the MIME standards and generally are hidden from users of email software.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The IETF has defined a framework for internationalized email using UTF-8, and has updated several protocols in accordance with that framework.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The adoption of Unicode in email has been very slow.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Some East Asian text is still encoded in encodings such as ISO-2022, and some devices, such as mobile phones, still cannot correctly handle Unicode data.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Many major free mail providers such as Yahoo!
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Mail, Gmail, and Outlook.com support it.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] All W3C recommendations have used Unicode as their *document character set* since HTML 4.0.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Web browsers have supported Unicode, especially UTF-8, for many years.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] There used to be display problems resulting primarily from font related issues; e.g. v6 and older of Microsoft Internet Explorer did not render many code points unless explicitly told to use a font that contains them.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] HTML characters manifest either directly as bytes according to the document's encoding, if the encoding supports them, or users may write them as numeric character references based on the character's Unicode code point.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] When specifying URIs, for example as URLs in HTTP requests, non-ASCII characters must be percent-encoded.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Unicode is not in principle concerned with fonts *per se*, seeing them as implementation choices.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Any given character may have many allographs, from the more common bold, italic and base letterforms to complex decorative styles.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] A font is "Unicode compliant" if the glyphs in the font can be accessed using code points defined in *The Unicode Standard*.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The standard does not specify a minimum number of characters that must be included in the font; some fonts have quite a small repertoire.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Free and retail fonts based on Unicode are widely available, since TrueType and OpenType support Unicode (and Web Open Font Format (WOFF and WOFF2) is based on those).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] These font formats map Unicode code points to glyphs, but OpenType and TrueType font files are restricted to 65,535 glyphs.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Collection files provide a "gap mode" mechanism for overcoming this limit in a single font file.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] (Each font within the collection still has the 65,535 limit, however.) A TrueType Collection file would typically have a file extension of ".ttc".
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Thousands of fonts exist on the market, but fewer than a dozen fonts—sometimes described as "pan-Unicode" fonts—attempt to support the majority of Unicode's character repertoire.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Instead, Unicode-based fonts typically focus on supporting only basic ASCII and particular scripts or sets of characters or symbols.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Furthermore, designing a consistent set of rendering instructions for tens of thousands of glyphs constitutes a monumental task; such a venture passes the point of diminishing returns for most typefaces.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Unicode partially addresses the newline problem that occurs when trying to read a text file on different platforms.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Unicode defines a large number of characters that conforming applications should recognize as line terminators.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] In terms of the newline, Unicode introduced U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] This was an attempt to provide a Unicode solution to encoding paragraphs and lines semantically, potentially replacing all of the various platform solutions.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] In doing so, Unicode does provide a way around the historical platform-dependent solutions.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Nonetheless, few if any Unicode solutions have adopted these Unicode line and paragraph separators as the sole canonical line ending characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] However, a common approach to solving this issue is through newline normalization.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] This is achieved with the Cocoa text system in macOS and also with W3C XML and HTML recommendations.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] In this approach, every possible newline character is converted internally to a common newline (which one does not really matter since it is an internal operation just for rendering).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] In other words, the text system can correctly treat the character as a newline, regardless of the input's actual encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The Ideographic Research Group (IRG) is tasked with advising the Consortium and ISO regarding Han unification, or Unihan, especially the further addition of CJK unified and compatibility ideographs to the repertoire.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The IRG is composed of experts from each region that has historically used Chinese characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] However, despite the deliberation within the committee, Han unification has consistently been one of the most contested aspects of *The Unicode Standard* since the genesis of the project.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Unicode's character model for CJK characters was based on the unification criteria used by JIS X 0208, as well as those developed by the Association for a Common Chinese Code in China.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Due to the standard's principle of encoding semantic instead of stylistic variants, Unicode has received criticism for not assigning code points to certain rare and archaic kanji variants, possibly complicating processing of ancient and uncommon Japanese names.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Since it places particular emphasis on Chinese, Japanese and Korean sharing many characters in common, Han unification is also sometimes perceived as treating the three as the same thing.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Less-frequently-used alternative encodings exist, often predating Unicode, with character models differing from this paradigm, aimed at preserving the various stylistic differences between regional and/or nonstandard character forms.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] One example is the TRON Code favored by some users for handling historical Japanese text, though not widely adopted among the Japanese public.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Another is the CCCII encoding adopted by library systems in Hong Kong, Taiwan and the United States.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] These have their own drawbacks in general use, leading to the Big5 encoding (introduced in 1984, four years after CCCII) having become more common than CCCII outside of library systems.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Although work at Apple based on Research Libraries Group's CJK Thesaurus, which was used to maintain the EACC variant of CCCII, was one of the direct predecessors of Unicode's Unihan set, Unicode adopted the JIS-style unification model.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The earliest version of Unicode had a repertoire of fewer than 21,000 Han characters, largely limited to those in relatively common modern usage.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] As of version 17.0, the standard now encodes more than 101,000 Han characters, and work is continuing to add thousands more—largely historical and dialectal variant characters used throughout the Sinosphere.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Modern typefaces provide a means to address some of the practical issues in depicting unified Han characters with various regional graphical representations.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The 'locl' OpenType table allows a renderer to select a different glyph for each code point based on the text locale.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The Unicode variation sequences can also provide in-text annotations for a desired glyph selection; this requires registration of the specific variant in the Ideographic Variation Database.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The same OpenType 'locl' technique is used.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] For use in the Turkish alphabet and Azeri alphabet, Unicode includes a separate dotless lowercase I (ı) and a dotted uppercase I (İ).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] However, the usual ASCII letters are used for the lowercase dotted i and the uppercase dotless I, matching how they are handled in the earlier ISO 8859-9.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] As such, case-insensitive comparisons for those languages have to use different rules than case-insensitive comparisons for other languages using the Latin script.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] This can have security implications if, for example, sanitization code or access control relies on case-insensitive comparison.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] By contrast, the Icelandic eth (ð), the barred D (đ) and the retroflex D (ɖ), which usually look the same in uppercase (Đ), are given the opposite treatment, and encoded separately in both letter-cases (in contrast to the earlier ISO 6937, which unifies the uppercase forms).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Although it allows for case-insensitive comparison without needing to know the language of the text, this approach also has issues, requiring security measures relating to homoglyph attacks.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Whether the lowercase letter I is expected to retain its tittle when a diacritic applies also depends on local conventions.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Unicode has a large number of homoglyphs, many of which look very similar or identical to ASCII letters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Substitution of these can make an identifier or URL that looks correct, but directs to a different location than expected.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Additionally, homoglyphs can also be used for manipulating the output of natural language processing (NLP) systems.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Mitigation requires disallowing these characters, displaying them differently, or requiring that they resolve to the same identifier; all of this is complicated due to the huge and constantly changing set of characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] A security advisory was released in 2021 by two researchers, one from the University of Cambridge and the other from the University of Edinburgh, in which they assert that the BiDi marks can be used to make large sections of code do something different from what they appear to do.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] In response, code editors started highlighting marks to indicate forced text-direction changes.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The UTF-8 and UTF-16 encodings do not accept all possible sequences of code units.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Implementations vary in what they do when reading an invalid sequence, which has led to security bugs.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Unicode was designed to provide code-point-by-code-point round-trip format conversion to and from any preexisting character encodings, so that text files in older character sets can be converted to Unicode and then back and get back the same file, without employing context-dependent interpretation.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] That has meant that inconsistent legacy architectures, such as combining diacritics and precomposed characters, both exist in Unicode, giving more than one method of representing some text.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] This is most pronounced in the three different encoding forms for Korean Hangul.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Since version 3.0, any precomposed characters that can be represented by a combined sequence of already existing characters can no longer be added to the standard to preserve interoperability between software using different versions of Unicode.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Injective mappings must be provided between characters in existing legacy character sets and characters in Unicode to facilitate conversion to Unicode and allow interoperability with legacy software.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Some Japanese computer programmers objected to Unicode because it requires them to separate the use of U+005C \ REVERSE SOLIDUS (backslash) and U+00A5 ¥ YEN SIGN, which was mapped to 0x5C in JIS X 0201, and a lot of legacy code exists with this usage.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] (This encoding also replaces tilde '~' 0x7E with macron '¯', now 0xAF.) The separation of these characters exists in ISO 8859-1, from long before Unicode.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Indic scripts such as Tamil and Devanagari are each allocated only 128 code points, matching the ISCII standard.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The correct rendering of Unicode Indic text requires transforming the stored logical order characters into visual order and the forming of ligatures (also known as conjuncts) out of components.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Some local scholars argued in favor of assignments of Unicode code points to these ligatures, going against the practice for other writing systems, though Unicode contains some Arabic and other ligatures for backward compatibility purposes only.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Encoding of any new ligatures in Unicode will not happen, in part, because the set of ligatures is font-dependent, and Unicode is an encoding independent of font variations.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The same kind of issue arose for the Tibetan script in 2003 when the Standardization Administration of China proposed encoding 956 precomposed Tibetan syllables, but these were rejected for encoding by the relevant ISO committee (ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 2).
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Thai alphabet support has been criticized for its ordering of Thai characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] The vowels เ, แ, โ, ใ, ไ that are written to the left of the preceding consonant are in visual order instead of phonetic order, unlike the Unicode representations of other Indic scripts.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] This complication is due to Unicode inheriting the Thai Industrial Standard 620, which worked in the same way, and was the way in which Thai had always been written on keyboards.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] This ordering problem complicates the Unicode collation process slightly, requiring table lookups to reorder Thai characters for collation.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Even if Unicode had adopted encoding according to spoken order, it would still be problematic to collate words in dictionary order.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] E.g., the word แสดง [sa dɛːŋ] "perform" starts with a consonant cluster "สด" (with an inherent vowel for the consonant "ส"), the vowel แ-, in spoken order would come after the ด, but in a dictionary, the word is collated as it is written, with the vowel following the ส.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Characters with diacritical marks can generally be represented either as a single precomposed character or as a decomposed sequence of a base letter plus one or more non-spacing marks.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] Similarly, underdots, as needed in the romanization of Indic languages, will often be placed incorrectly.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] While Unicode defines the script designator (name) to be "Phags_Pa", in that script's character names, a hyphen is added: U+A840 ꡀ PHAGS-PA LETTER KA.
[src:encodings-serialization/unicode-p02] This, however, is not an anomaly, but the rule: hyphens are replaced by underscores in script designators.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] UTF-8 supports all 1,112,064 valid Unicode code points using a variable-width encoding of one to four one-byte (8-bit) code units.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Code points with lower numerical values, which tend to occur more frequently, are encoded using fewer bytes.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] It was designed for backward compatibility with ASCII: the first 128 characters of Unicode, which correspond one-to-one with ASCII, are encoded using a single byte with the same binary value as ASCII, so that a UTF-8-encoded file using only those characters is identical to an ASCII file.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Most software designed for any extended ASCII can read and write UTF-8, and this results in fewer internationalization issues than any alternative text encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] UTF-8 is dominant for all countries/languages on the internet, is used in most standards, often the only allowed encoding, and is supported by all modern operating systems and programming languages.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) set out to compose a universal multi-byte character set in 1989.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The draft ISO 10646 standard contained a non-required annex called UTF-1 that provided a byte stream encoding of its 32-bit code points.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] In July 1992, the X/Open committee XoJIG was looking for a better encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Dave Prosser of Unix System Laboratories submitted a proposal for one that had faster implementation characteristics and introduced the improvement that 7-bit ASCII characters would *only* represent themselves; multi-byte sequences would only include bytes with the high bit set.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The name *File System Safe UCS Transformation Format* (*FSS-UTF*) and most of the text of this proposal were later preserved in the final specification.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] In August 1992, this proposal was circulated by an IBM X/Open representative to interested parties.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] A modification by Ken Thompson of the Plan 9 operating system group at Bell Labs made it self-synchronizing, letting a reader start anywhere and immediately detect character boundaries, at the cost of being somewhat less bit-efficient than the previous proposal.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] It also abandoned the use of biases that prevented overlong encodings.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Thompson's design was outlined on September 2, 1992, on a placemat in a New Jersey diner with Rob Pike.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] In the following days, Pike and Thompson implemented it and updated Plan 9 to use it throughout, and then communicated their success back to X/Open, which accepted it as the specification for FSS-UTF.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] UTF-8 was first officially presented at the USENIX conference in San Diego, from January 25 to 29, 1993.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The Internet Engineering Task Force adopted UTF-8 in its Policy on Character Sets and Languages in RFC 2277 (BCP 18) for future internet standards work in January 1998, replacing Single Byte Character Sets such as Latin-1 in older RFCs.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Earlier standards for UTF-8, like RFC 2279, could encode up to 31 bits in 6 bytes.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] UTF-8 encodes code points in one to four bytes, depending on the value of the code point.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The first 128 code points (ASCII) need 1 byte.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The next 1,920 code points need two bytes to encode, which covers the remainder of almost all Latin-script alphabets, and also IPA extensions, Greek, Cyrillic, Coptic, Armenian, Hebrew, Arabic, Syriac, Thaana and N'Ko alphabets, as well as Combining Diacritical Marks.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Three bytes are needed for the remaining 61,440 codepoints of the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP), including most Chinese, Japanese and Korean characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Four bytes are needed for the 1,048,576 non-BMP code points, which include emoji, less common CJK characters, and other useful characters.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] UTF-8 is a *prefix code* and it is unnecessary to read past the last byte of a code point to decode it.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Unlike many earlier multi-byte text encodings such as Shift-JIS, it is *self-synchronizing* so searches for short strings or characters are possible; and the start of a code point can be found from a random position by backing up at most 3 bytes.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The values chosen for the lead bytes means sorting a list of UTF-8 strings puts them in the same order as sorting UTF-32 strings.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Using a row in the above table to encode a code point less than "First code point" (thus using more bytes than necessary) is termed an *overlong encoding*.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] These are a security problem because they allow character sequences to bypass other security validations like the blocking of `../` or of malicious JavaScript.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] There have been numerous high-profile vulnerabilities involving overlong encodings reported in products such as Microsoft's IIS web server and Apache's Tomcat servlet container.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Overlong encodings should therefore be considered an error and never decoded.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Not all sequences of bytes are valid UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Many of the first UTF-8 decoders would decode these, ignoring incorrect bits.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Carefully crafted invalid UTF-8 could make them either skip or create ASCII characters such as NUL, slash, or quotes, leading to security vulnerabilities.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] RFC 3629 states "Implementations of the decoding algorithm MUST protect against decoding invalid sequences." *The Unicode Standard* requires decoders to: "... treat any ill-formed code unit sequence as an error condition.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] It was common to throw an exception or truncate the string at an error but this turns what would otherwise be harmless errors (i.e.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] "file not found") into a denial of service, for instance early versions of Python 3.0 would exit immediately if the command line or environment variables contained invalid UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Most code now replaces each error with a single code point (such as U+FFFD � REPLACEMENT CHARACTER) and continue decoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Some decoders consider the sequence E1,A0,20 (a truncated 3-byte code followed by a space) as a single error.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] This is not a good idea as a search for a space character would find the one hidden in the error.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Since Unicode 6 (October 2010) the standard (chapter 3) has recommended a "best practice" where the error is either one continuation byte, or ends at the first byte that is disallowed, so E1,A0,20 is a two-byte error followed by a space.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] An error is no more than three bytes long, never contains the start of a valid character, and there are 21,952 different possible errors.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Many decoders instead make *each* byte be an error, in which case E1,A0,20 is *two* errors followed by a space; there are now only 128 different errors which makes it practical to store the errors in the output string, or replace them with characters from a legacy encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Only a small subset of possible byte strings are error-free UTF-8: several bytes cannot appear, a byte with the high bit set cannot be alone, and in a truly random string a byte with a high bit set has only a 1⁄15 chance of starting a valid UTF-8 character.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] This has the consequence of making it easy to detect if a legacy text encoding is accidentally used instead of UTF-8, making conversion of a system to UTF-8 easier and avoiding the need to require a Byte Order Mark or any other metadata.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Since RFC 3629 (November 2003), the high and low surrogates used by UTF-16 (U+D800 through U+DFFF) are not legal Unicode values, and their UTF-8 encodings must be treated as an invalid byte sequence.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] These encodings all start with 0xED followed by 0xA0 or higher.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] This rule is often ignored as surrogates are allowed in Windows filenames and this means there must be a way to store them in a string.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] UTF-8 that allows these surrogate halves has been (informally) called *WTF-8*, for "wobbly transformation format", while another variation that also encodes all non-BMP characters as two surrogates (6 bytes instead of 4) is called *CESU-8*.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The chart below gives the detailed meaning of each byte in a stream encoded in UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] If the Unicode byte-order mark U+FEFF is at the start of a UTF-8 file, the first three bytes will be 0xEF, 0xBB, 0xBF.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The Unicode Standard neither requires nor recommends the use of the BOM for UTF-8, but warns that it may be encountered at the start of a file trans-coded from another encoding.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] While ASCII text encoded using UTF-8 is backward compatible with ASCII, this is not true when Unicode Standard recommendations are ignored and a BOM is added.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] A BOM can confuse software that isn't prepared for it but can otherwise accept UTF-8, e.g. programming languages that permit non-ASCII bytes in string literals but not at the start of the file.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Nevertheless, there was and still is software that always inserts a BOM when writing UTF-8, and refuses to correctly interpret UTF-8 unless the first character is a BOM (or the file only contains ASCII).
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] For a long time there was considerable argument as to whether it was better to process text in UTF-16 or in UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The primary advantage of UTF-16 is that the Windows API required it for access to all Unicode characters (UTF-8 was not fully supported in Windows until May 2019).
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] This caused several libraries such as Qt to also use UTF-16 strings which propagates this requirement to non-Windows platforms.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] In the early days of Unicode, there were no characters greater than U+FFFF and combining characters were rarely used, so the 16-bit encoding was effectively fixed-size.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Some believed fixed-size encoding could make processing more efficient, but any such advantages were lost as soon as UTF-16 became variable width as well.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The code points U+0800–U+FFFF take 3 bytes in UTF-8 but only 2 in UTF-16.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] This led to the idea that text in Chinese and other languages would take more space in UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] However, text is only larger if there are more of these code points than 1-byte ASCII code points, and this rarely happens in real-world documents due to markup, along with spaces, newlines, digits, punctuation, English words, etc..
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] UTF-8 has the advantages of being trivial to retrofit to any system that could handle an extended ASCII, not having byte-order problems, and taking about half the space for any language using mostly Latin letters.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] UTF-8 has been the most common encoding for the World Wide Web since 2008.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] As of January 2026, UTF-8 is used by 98.9% of surveyed web sites.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Although many pages only use ASCII characters to display content, very few websites now declare their encoding to only be ASCII instead of UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Virtually all countries and languages have 95% or more use of UTF-8 encodings on the web.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] JSON exchange requires it (without a byte-order mark (BOM)).
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] UTF-8 is also required by the WHATWG for HTML and DOM specifications, which states "UTF-8 encoding is the most appropriate encoding for interchange of Unicode", and the Internet Mail Consortium recommends that all e‑mail programs be able to display and create mail using UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The World Wide Web Consortium recommends UTF-8 as the default encoding in XML and HTML (and not just using UTF-8, also declaring it in metadata), "even when all characters are in the ASCII range ...
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Using non-UTF-8 encodings can have unexpected results".
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Version 5.3 of the W3C HTML specification and the current Living Standard by WHATWG both require UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Many software programs have the ability to read/write UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] It may require the user to change options from the normal settings, or may require a BOM (byte-order mark) as the first character to read the file.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Examples of software supporting UTF-8 include Microsoft Word, Microsoft Excel (Office 2003 and later), Google Drive, LibreOffice, and most databases.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Software that "defaults" to UTF-8 (meaning it writes it without the user changing settings, and it reads it without a BOM) has become more common since 2010.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Windows Notepad, in all currently supported versions of Windows, defaults to writing UTF-8 without a BOM (a change from Windows 7 *Notepad*), bringing it into line with most other text editors.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Some system files on Windows 11 require UTF-8 with no requirement for a BOM, and almost all files on macOS and most Linux distributions are required to be UTF-8 without a BOM.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Programming languages that default to UTF-8 for I/O include Ruby 3.0, R 4.2.2, Raku and Java 18.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Python 3.15 makes UTF-8 the default for I/O; previous versions require an option to `open()` to read/write UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] C++23 adopted UTF-8 as the only portable source code file format.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Backwards compatibility is a serious impediment to changing code and APIs using UTF-16 to use UTF-8, but this is happening.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The default string primitive in Go, Julia, Rust, Swift (since version 5), and PyPy uses UTF-8 internally in all cases.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Python (since version 3.3) uses UTF-8 internally for Python C API extensions and sometimes for strings and a future version of Python is planned to store strings as UTF-8 by default.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Modern versions of Microsoft Visual Studio use UTF-8 internally.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] All currently supported versions of Microsoft SQL Server support UTF-8 for importing and exporting, and in addition all on mainstream support, i.e. since SQL Server 2019, support UTF-8 internally, and using it results in a 35% speed increase, and "nearly 50% reduction in storage requirements".
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Java internally uses UTF-16 for the `char` data type and, consequentially, the `Character`, `String`, and `StringBuffer` classes, but for I/O uses *"Modified UTF-8"*, which is the same as CESU-8, except the null character U+0000 uses the two-byte overlong encoding 0xC0 0x80 instead of just 0x00.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Modified UTF-8 strings never contain any actual null bytes but can contain all Unicode code points including U+0000, which allows such strings (with a null byte appended) to be processed by traditional null-terminated string functions.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Java reads and writes normal UTF-8 to files and streams, but it uses Modified UTF-8 for object serialization, for the Java Native Interface, and for embedding constant strings in Java class files.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The dex format defined by Dalvik also uses the same modified UTF-8 to represent string values.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Tcl also uses the same modified UTF-8 as Java for internal representation of Unicode data, but uses strict CESU-8 for external data.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The Raku programming language (formerly Perl 6) uses `utf-8` encoding by default for I/O (Perl 5 also supports it); though that choice in Raku also implies "normalization into Unicode NFC (normalization form canonical).
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] In some cases the user will want to ensure no normalization is done; for this "`utf8-c8`" can be used.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] That *UTF-8 Clean-8* variant, implemented by Raku, is an encoder/decoder that preserves bytes as is (even illegal UTF-8 sequences) and allows for Normal Form Grapheme synthetics.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Version 3 of the Python programming language treats each byte of an invalid UTF-8 bytestream as an error (see also changes with new UTF-8 mode in Python 3.7); this gives 128 different possible errors.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Extensions have been created to allow any byte sequence that is assumed to be UTF-8 to be losslessly transformed to UTF-16 or UTF-32, by translating the 128 possible error bytes to 128 reserved code points, and transforming those code points back to error bytes to output UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The most common approach is to translate the codes to U+DC80...U+DCFF which are low (trailing) surrogate values and thus "invalid" UTF-16, as used by Python's PEP 383 (or "surrogateescape") approach.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] NumPy version 2.0, and its file formats, support UTF-8 (adding StringDType for it).
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Another encoding called MirBSD OPTU-8/16 converts them to U+EF80...U+EFFF in a Private Use Area.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] In either approach, the byte value is encoded in the low eight bits of the output code point.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] These encodings are needed if invalid UTF-8 is to survive translation to and then back from the UTF-16 used internally by Python, and as Unix filenames can contain invalid UTF-8 it is necessary for this to work.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Most file systems on Unix-like systems can use UTF-8 to encode file names, as looking up file names is done by comparing the bytes of file names.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Linux's ext4 and macOS's APFS file systems support case-insensitive file name lookups, which require that the encoding of file names be specified; ext4 supports UTF-8 and uses it by default, and APFS requires UTF-8.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Apple's older HFS Plus uses UTF-16 for file names, but uses UTF-8 in symbolic links.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] Windows' filesystem, NTFS, uses UTF-16 for file names.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The official name for the encoding is `UTF-8`, the spelling used in all Unicode Consortium documents.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] The hyphen-minus is required and no spaces are allowed.
[src:encodings-serialization/utf-8] They are all the same in their general mechanics, with the main differences being on issues such as allowed range of code point values and safe handling of invalid input.
